commit_message:
Add feature to update/replace yum configuration

This change is required in order to build images with
yum-based distros with custom/updated packages, 
same functional is available for apt-based distros with elements/apt-sources

DIB_YUM_CONF should be used to override yum.conf, e.g:
    DIB_YUM_CONF=/etc/yum.conf

To override yum repos completely use DIB_REPLACE_YUM_REPOS, e.g.:
    DIB_REPLACE_YUM_REPOS=/etc/repos.d/

To add additional yum repos to existing one:
    DIB_ADD_YUM_REPOS=/etc/repos.d/

Change-Id: Ibe38dfa4564c91fb6452618bc6f52e3cc209f21c

commit_message:
libvirt: Remove outdated comment from a docstring

This fix

    http://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;h=0f9e67bfad (python: return
    dictionary without value in case of no blockjob)

is backported (a while ago) to libvirt maintenance branch 1.0.5-maint:

    http://libvirt.org/git/?p=libvirt.git;a=commit;h=c43e7e20fc

Remove the comment that states that the backport is pending.

Change-Id: Ib583219f9a2c1b03e0f70d5ab1d6c7df29daecc9

commit_message:
Cinder api service doesn't handle SIGHUP properly

When SIGHUP signal is sent to cinder-api service, it doesn't complete
processing of all pending requests before terminating all the
processes.

This change is a copy of Abhishek Kekane's fix for nova api.

Change-Id: I049d2aa2f3ad1fe388e00213a71f374803ed409a
Closes-Bug: #1334647

commit_message:
Retry on closing of luks encrypted volume in case device is busy

We're seeing races in the gate on detach of an encrypted volume where
the device is busy so the detach fails, which causes the delete of the
volume on the cinder side to fail because the volume is still in use and
then Tempest times out waiting for the volume to be deleted.

This simply adds a retry to close the encryption device.  I use
attempts=3 since that's what we use for lvremove.

Closes-Bug: #1374458

Change-Id: Ia0667da7dee247ba8c3338b296244b2a71d1045d
(cherry picked from commit eef97cdf4bb7f426d7feb394ef54510db8b1656b)

commit_message:
Fix dynamic select layout when help block is displayed

This fixes the layout of the dynamic select widget when the help
block is displayed. To reproduce this error you must be using the
keystone v2 API so that the Primary Project field will be required
when creating a user. If you leave it blank when submitting the
form the help block will be displayed.

Closes-Bug: #1361725
Change-Id: Ied4bb5d22b7e8a1948330503516cba2aa016417f

After quite a bit of playing around with horizon with and without this patch, it would seem that this patch is not at fault, the problem exists in master. The issue is intermittent and it only seems to happen to me on a fresh session. 
Steps I followed on master: 
1) Sign out of horizon,
2) Sign into horizon, 
3) Go to Admin->System->Images,
4) Go to Page 2 of images table,
5) Apply the 'Image Name =' filter to match one of the images, 
6) Notice that we are still on the second page, 
7) Delete filter text box contents, 
8) Re-click filter

Thanks Sam. Glad we figured out this all pertains to the special case Project filter which does not get applied using the API. Looks like there are still a couple weird things going on with the Project filter:

1) It does not redirect back to the first page on the first filter applied.
You need a clean session to see this. Go to page two and apply a filter. The update to the "changed" variable in horizon.tables.views.get_server_filter_info() that we talked about previously seems to fix that for me. Would need to verify there are no side effects though.
	changed = (filter_string != filter_string_session)
	
2) Paging is independent of the filter since that happens in the API, it's filtered afterward in the table.
...ugh. This is technically correct since the Project filter is applied per page, but man is it confusing. We may not have a good solution to this until all the paging / sorting / filtering is moved to horizon (that really is supposed to happen). Honestly I think we should just get rid of the support for non-API server filters on paged tables. They just don't make sense. To see this in action just apply a Project filter that matches nothing when there are multiple pages.

Another thing to think about is whether the nova servers API does have support for querying on the project. I didn't think it did but if that's the case it might solve all our problems.'}, {'account_id': 9647, 'date': '2014-09-25 21:40:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Those other issues aside, the filter does seem to get applied on the first try, which is what this patch is intending to fix. commit_message:
Ensure DataTableView applies filter after redirect

Non-API bound filters were not persisting across pages changes,
this patch adds an additional check to make sure the DataTable looks
for any non api bound filters in the session and applies them on page load.
Also added some logic to make Project filter in Admin->Instances API
bound using the tenant_id.

Change-Id: Ieab9f2b92b59401809725a4f37628757dc4c8f13
Closes-Bug: 1369014

commit_message:
SELinux: Update keepalived custom policy

Found additional denials with keepalived unable able to read /proc.
Updated the custom policy to allow keepalived to read /proc.

These additional changes are temporary and should be removed
when the denials are fixed in the upstream selinux-policy.

Partial-Bug: 1379079
Change-Id: I30d74f80386e908822fcc6ff5ac3d4ae90fc4e27

commit_message:
threadgroup: add support for automatic expansion of thread pool

If thread_pool_size is 0, automatically expand the underlying
greenthread pool to fairly accomodate all spawned threads.

blueprint expand-eventlet-greenpool

Change-Id: I75129caf0c090e5e6dc0c56aea1021bda61ec0dd
Related-Bug: 1372049

[{'created': '2014-10-23 21:48:46.000000000', 'message': 'Add pbr to dependency list

We use pbr to install stevedore, and because of the way setuptools deals
with install-time requirements we also need to include it as a runtime
dependency to ensure it is installed by pip and not easy_install.

Change-Id: I0a39bb50218a1a7cdb2d42fb474a9b8f6d6ac32a
Closes-Bug: #1384919
'}]
commit_message:
Add pbr to dependency list

We use pbr to install stevedore, and because of the way setuptools deals
with install-time requirements we also need to include it as a runtime
dependency to ensure it is installed by pip and not easy_install.

Change-Id: I0a39bb50218a1a7cdb2d42fb474a9b8f6d6ac32a
Closes-Bug: #1384919

commit_message:
Switch to oslo.config

The config module in oslo-incubator has been replaced by oslo.config.
Projects need to switch completely to oslo.config for kilo.

This patch does:
* Register options with oslo.config (new file manila/opts.py)
* Generate the config file using oslo-config-generator
* Remove obsoleted entries for this from openstack-common.conf
* Remove oslo-incubator config files

Change-Id: I30b594423c08782e13a1f615099ae65f997a8551
Closes-Bug: #1382183

commit_message:
Make rbd store's pool handling more universal

Currently we ignore the pool part of the location throughout the rbd store code.
If there is a pool specified, use that. Otherwise we can still fall back to the
configured pool.

This is a required change if we want to support ephemeral disk snapshotting later on
as in that scenario the ephemeral pool might be a different pool from images pool,
yet we're going to need to reference the snapshot of a disk in the ephemeral pool.

Change-Id: Ie415667a809975948c8cfb71ec63a0905995fa67
Closes-Bug: 1368128

Added cancel before deleting job execution

Now delete method will stop running job before
deleting job execution object in database

commit_message:
Breakdown CSS: split styling for table inline edits

Removed the nonexistent halflings image reference.  Some inline editing
functionalities are broken after bootstrap patch (not because of this
change!). These issues will be address with another patch.

Change-Id: If349c6e4bd8afeded061a21561ea911bcb472abe
Closes-Bug: #1379519
Partially-Implements: blueprint css-breakdown

commit_message:
Use service tenant id for Ironic agent swift auth

Config of ironic conductor currently references a non-existent variable.
This corrects it by obtaining and using the correct tenant id.

Change-Id: I4340f75b2b22a8fd3fd8dd5cb30d7e91bce4f654

commit_message:
Fixes nothing is displayed if volume metadata is empty problem

If volume metadata is empty, nothing is displayed below "Metadata"
<h4> heading in the volume detail page. So, this patch fixes this
problem by displaying "None".

Change-Id: I0302e47cc8c9e471972ef7c249d54582242b5390
Closes-bug: #1382876

commit_message:
Fix dict iteration usage

When iterating a dict, it is redundant to create a list of keys
using the keys() method. Using iteritems() lets us iterate a dict more
efficiently.

Closes-Bug: #1384990

Change-Id: If8ffcf19129430506020adb9716a7dfdda9d98f5

file object.

commit_message:
Fix tempest compatibility

Decorator "safe_setup" was removed in Tempest project, we need to remove its
usage to fix compatibility.

Gerrit commit: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122531/
Tempest commit: https://github.com/openstack/tempest/commit/c27feb85

Change-Id: I1c9a9a668b3d7761c07af72aff8415b86ffaa8a5
Closes-Bug: #1378677

commit_message:
Close files on server create, add tests

The files opened for the --files and --user-data options were never
closed, potentially leaking memory in a long-running client. Close
them if they are file objects.

Add a couple of basic tests for server create.

Change-Id: I1658b0caa2d6af17308149cb52196ee28266ddf2

commit_message:
Freeze mccabe's version for hacking

mccabe has some drastic changes on master that will not introduce
backwards incompatible behaviour but will make the tool more accurately
compute complexity for various situations. To prevent surprises Joe
Gordon and I have decided to freeze the version now.

Change-Id: I768b785cb61172eb857a7710064e262f007dd138

User's don't know what a plugin is.

* Internally, os_auth_type and/or auth_type represents what the
  user supplied.
* auth_plugin_name is the name of the selected plugin
* auth_plugin is the actual plugin object

Plugin selection process:
* if --os-auth-type is supplied:
  * if it matches against an available plugin, done
  * (if it can map to an availble plugin type, done; TODO in a followup)

commit_message:
Change --os-auth-plugin to --os-auth-type

User's don't know what a plugin is.

* Internally, os_auth_type and/or auth_type represents what the
  user supplied.
* auth_plugin_name is the name of the selected plugin
* auth_plugin is the actual plugin object

Plugin selection process:
* if --os-auth-type is supplied:
  * if it matches against an available plugin, done
  * (if it can map to an availble plugin type, done; TODO in a followup)
* if --os-auth-type is not supplied:
  * if --os-url and --os-token are supplied, select 'token_endpoint'
  * if --os-username supplied, select identity_api_version + 'password'
  * if --os-token supplied, select identity_api_version + 'token'

Change-Id: Ice4535214e311ebf924087cf77f6d84d76f5f3ee

commit_message:
Fix issue for using clients configuration when component clients unset

Since component clients options are already registered in heat.common.config, when
the [clients] are configured with options like ca_cert while [clients_glance], [clients_cinder]
without configured these options, getattr call will return None instead of raising exception.
Fix this issue so that Heat can load the common clients configurations when clients component
sections not set.

Change-Id: Ic3dc44017c55e4437181e3b06f20640b899185cc
Closes-Bug: #1385021

commit_message:
iso element to use 'search --label' for grub

Current iso element uses 'search --file' to find the
grub root.  This is a wrong approach as it may find
some other partition containing /vmlinuz. Instead modify
it to search for grub root by the label of ISO image.

Closes-Bug: 1384826
Change-Id: Id4217be3420597bed2f80a96788928259ec91582

commit_message:
Fix the path in the alarm_definition link

Fix JAH-772, there were two slashes in a row in the URI

Also, I noticed while updating the documenation that the path was
missing the v2.0.

Change-Id: Icbd54dc6b837e2f6025bdae3950874a5daaf8d30

commit_message:
Fix to setup.cfg for dateutil

Previously we had not updated setup.cfg to properly install dateutil.
All the tests ran fine, but 'python setup.py install' did not put
dateutil in the proper place, which made the server fail when installed.

Change-Id: Icc468ff41c0d1a70c5dccb9966ce7ed41207c67e

commit_message:
Configuration file plugins support for nailgun

    - Task serialization logic for pre/post hooks
    - PluginSerializer object added
    - API for interaction with Plugins db schema
    General API requests supported
    GET/POST /plugins
    GET/PUT/DELETE /plugins/<plugin_id>
    - Plugins and ClustersPlugins db models added
    ClusterPlugins used to identify enabled plugins for a
    given cluster
    - Configuration uploading logic stored in Plugin wrapper

Co-authored-by: Dima Shulyak <dshulyak@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Evgeniy L <eli@mirantis.com>

implements: blueprint cinder-neutron-plugins-in-fuel
Change-Id: I986f5be9ed3c3adaf7583d1bfc546cbe705db9ec

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-20 15:01:42.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor rally verify cmd

Class `verification.verifiers.tempest.Tempest` contains next changes:
  Output from installation of virtual environment is not useful for users,
  so visibility of this output was changed and now only in debug mode it can
  be printed.

  Two variables contain word 'tempest' in their names. This is redundant,
  so they were renamed:
    Tempest.tempest_base_path => Tempest.base_repo
    Tempest.tempest_path => Tempest.path

  Construction "os.path.join(Tempest.path, some_path)" was moved to method
  `Tempest.join_path`, since it used in many places.

  Method `Tempest.parse_results` should be static, because it needed inner
  variable `Tempest.log_file_raw`, so this was fixed.

Change-Id: I08a52a1e3ceb468ba619049573bcfe642aecbcaf
'}, {'created': '2014-10-21 13:13:07.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor rally verify cmd

'}, {'created': '2014-10-22 10:59:39.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor tempest verification and tests for it

Class `verification.verifiers.tempest.Tempest` contains next changes:
  Output from installation of virtual environment is not useful for users,
  so visibility of this output was changed and now only in debug mode it
  will be printed.

  The status of verification will be changed to 'FAILED' if something will
  go wrong in subproccess.call

  Two variables contain word 'tempest' in their names. This is redundant,
  so they were renamed:
    Tempest.tempest_base_path => Tempest.base_repo
    Tempest.tempest_path => Tempest.path

  Construction "os.path.join(Tempest.path, some_path)" was moved to method
  `Tempest.join_path`, since it used in many places.

  Method `Tempest.parse_results` should be static, because it needed inner
  variable `Tempest.log_file_raw`, so this was fixed.

Function `orchestrator.api.verify` should return verification object, so
that we can set verification uuid to global variable as it implemented in
tasks.

Tests for verification contains a lot of tests, so they are splitted
to separate classes(TempestVerifyTestCase, TempestInstallAndUninstallTestCase
and etc). Also, new tests were added.

Change-Id: I08a52a1e3ceb468ba619049573bcfe642aecbcaf

commit_message:
Refactor tempest verification and tests for it

Class `verification.verifiers.tempest.Tempest` contains next changes:
  Output from installation of virtual environment is not useful for users,
  so visibility of this output was changed and now only in debug mode it
  will be printed.

  The status of verification will be changed to 'FAILED' if something will
  go wrong in subproccess.call

  Two variables contain word 'tempest' in their names. This is redundant,
  so they were renamed:
    Tempest.tempest_base_path => Tempest.base_repo
    Tempest.tempest_path => Tempest._path

  Construction "os.path.join(Tempest.path, some_path)" was moved to method
  `Tempest.path`, since it used in many places.

  Method `Tempest.parse_results` should not be static, because it needed
  inner variable `Tempest.log_file_raw`, so this was fixed.

  "git remote update" is not needed in Tempest installation, so we can
  remove this call and decrease time of installation.

In `rally.cmd.commands.verify.start` command, several issues were fixed:
  First function argument changed to "set_name" instead of "deploy_id".
  Reason: "deploy_id" have default value, so it should be the first in
          arguments. It will simplify command for end-users(launch
          'rally verify start <set_name>' instead of
          'rally verify start --set <set_name>').

  Task commands have cool feature: save task_id in global variables, so
  results cmd can print the last task, without setting it id. This feature
  is ported in verification.

Tests for verification contains a lot of tests, so they are splitted
to separate classes(TempestVerifyTestCase, TempestInstallAndUninstallTestCase
and etc). Also, new tests were added.

Change-Id: I08a52a1e3ceb468ba619049573bcfe642aecbcaf

commit_message:
Remove storing of password in browser

Plaintext password was stored in localStorage. This was removed and replaced
by token.
Username is still stored -- we display it in the navigation bar.
Tests were updated to use only the token and a check for username in navbar
was added.

Change-Id: Id9a053e119f6826eda5472629f7d09e618297403
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments

commit_message:
Map CloudConfig attributes to CloudConfig.config

Treat the CloudConfig object as if it has the config attributes directly.
And add some simple tests.

This makes it easier to replace an argparse.Namespace() object with a
CloudConfig object.  It also might make initialization of some of the
default attributes unnecessary.  An example of this usage is in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129795/1/openstackclient/shell.py

Change-Id: I00ced540cf94742e8cb738f8f0767445ffeb4bfe

of space in long term.

commit_message:
Increased keystone token expiration time to 24h

Long lived token will allow to use it in OSTF tests and in
long running upgrade where 1h token might not be sufficient.
Such token will also improve user experience when we switch
to storing token instead of storing user credentials.

Change-Id: I81ba5c11034fca8a332ec2e92f1f9804523e14f6
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments

commit_message:
Remove usage of admin_token

* Added new tenant/project: services
* Added two new users with admin roles to 'services' project:
  ostf and nailgun
* Use generated passwords for ostf and nailgun keystone users and
  remove admin_token
* OSTF and nailgun will use their users to validate keystone tokens
 instead of admin_token
* Added new services and endpoints for keystone, ostf, nailgun. Now
 it's possible to use keystone service catalog to discover their URLs

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ibf64d83e7507b6b5d68d3d95837940e062d2aa31
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments

commit_message:
Sync modules from oslo-incubator

Sync the following modules with oslo-incubator commit
2acb6502268f7cc973c2b37ee49b73de81b8b69d :

- eventlet_backdoor
- fileutils
- log
- loopingcall
- policy
- processutils
- service
- versionutils

Use mask_password from strutils.

Remove excutils, jsonutils, strutils, and timeutils since those
modules aren't used anymore.

These modules are chosen because they're easy to sync. The goal of
the next sync is to remove the rest of the deprecated modules, but
this is blocked until Keystone uses the oslo.config config generator.

Change-Id: I7a03842d800a94a7a231da2a497be8937318857d

commit_message:
Use correct object when deleting

SwiftSignalHandle was using the client object instead
of the client plugin object to check for Not Found
during delete. Also normalized access to the client
and plugin as well as remove a few pep8 warning items.

Change-Id: Ib73cb3846feb6ccb2e45859458008a1701aa2231
Closes-Bug: #1382226

commit_message:
Allow to customize log_name for services

This patch allows us to customize log_name for:
- proxy-server
- container-server
- object-server
- account-server

Which may be usefull for log collecting/parsing. Defaults remain
as they were before the patch.

Change-Id: I173652ec5bbe8d4382e10db4510d91aebceacab5

commit_message:
Add fileutils module

The federation code uses the fileutils module from oslo-incubator,
so it needs to be in openstack-common.conf otherwise it will be
removed in a sync.

Change-Id: I6da4f026e15db4aaf0e634ede869687433acce92

commit_message:
Fixing validation exception for valid security group

Now casting the id of the allowed security group to a
six.text_type() to avoid type mismatching when using ids.

Change-Id: Iff2e442501d9c85c2b73c9a36114728830b04701
Closes-Bug:  #1384743

commit_message:
Add simple multi thread broker

To make creation/deletion of resources in different context it's very usefull
to use broker module. Where we are publishing to queue "tasks" and consuming them
from different threads.

In case of working with OpenStack resources we should cache initialized clients
and initialized clients can't be shared between threads.

So to be able to cache clients each thread has it's own *cache* dict

Co-authored-by: Mikhail Dubov <mdubov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Ic67bd45df375de98140c3fdd20a1af129f0886f0

commit_message:
Correcting error in NeutronClientRemoteWrapper._get_adapters

changes
* fixing the list comprehension in _get_adapters when aggregating all hosts
* adding tests for _get_adapters to test initial add of adapter and
  returning all adapters

Change-Id: I13c8b5a85c312a39a6b5d567390782cecef1ce9c
Closes-Bug: #1383904

commit_message:
Validate get_item for presence of a range key

Raise ValidationError if table schema has a range key
and get_item request misses a value for the range key

Change-Id: Iff3d72f0539e503476feb1e7400242057abc2e3d
Fixes-bug: 1290878

hash from the DB before a topology sync. This will ensure
that inconsistency will be detected if the topology sync
fails.

This logic was originally there to make sure the hash header
was not present on the topology sync call to the backend.
However, the hash header is ignored by the backend in a sync

commit_message:
Big Switch: Don't clear hash before sync

This patch removes the step of clearing the consistency
hash from the DB before a topology sync. This will ensure
that inconsistency will be detected if the topology sync
fails.

This logic was originally there to make sure the hash header
was not present on the topology sync call to the backend.
However, the hash header is ignored by the backend in a sync
call so it wasn't necessary.

Closes-Bug: #1379510
Change-Id: I2d58fa2aea3b692834d64192d06ace727c7df8a0
(cherry picked from commit 24e4110eb284078775496501ff81630eb1619c11)

commit_message:
Add manila specific hacking checks

Add manila specific hacking checks (copied over from nova) to test:
- [M319] Validate that debug level logs are not translated.
- [M323] Ensure that the _() function is explicitly imported to ensure
  proper translations.
- [M325] str() cannot be used on an exception.  Remove use or use
  six.text_type()
- [M326] Translated messages cannot be concatenated.  String should be
  included in translated message.

Also include some tests for the above (copied from nova and adjusted).

Rework HACKING.rst to remove the content that is in the global hacking
file and add in the manila specific rules.

Change-Id: I530609a183c81ba942623b73d5f62cd338b04211

commit_message:
Fix a response header bug in the error middleware

Coerce the Content-Length of the custom error message to a string, not an
integer.  Some pure Python WSGI servers aren't strict and violate the WSGI
specification by automatically converting the value to a string.  Apache,
however, *is* strict, and considers this a 500 Internal Error

Fixes bug 1306963

Change-Id: I9b82ceee096b00c21c3b230dc67701bc40629968
(cherry picked from commit 381d9ba941e93386000dd29b9426358efb7713f7)

commit_message:
Improve plugins and apply loading for runners and contexts plugins

Provide plugins loading for runners and contexts, improve samples.
Plugins now can be loaded from ~/.rally/plugins and /opt/rally/plugins
and any it's subdirectories.

Closes-Bug: #1320942

Change-Id: I213086e7eae17e297c398c301f5ed8d2331d951e

There is a situation, when  we request resource data
from db during loadbalancer resource deleting. If
there is no such data, NotFound exception raised and

commit_message:
Catch NotFound error during loadbalancer deleting

There is a situation, when  we request resource data
from db during loadbalancer resource deleting. If
there is no such data, NotFound exception raised and
stack delete failed with this error. To prevent this
behaviour, there is a need to catch NotFound exception
in delete method of loadbalancer.

Change-Id: Ie52bc3059e91bd25effc53bbd255bce6948509ac
Closes-bug: #1381700

commit_message:
Fix passing workflow input via UI

 * When we are using UI to pass workflow input
   to execution, we always pass it as json string.
   We need to prevent using extra json.dumps on string.

Change-Id: Ie11c342b305a1359f9a28d354230f515d36e7a0c

With few changes, GPFS and IBM NAS cinder drivers could support the proposed NFS security enhancements, except for one case - 'volume clone'. We need to create an intermediate file during a volume clone operation, which needs to be cleaned up once the cloned and the parent volumes are deleted. This operation needs to be performed as the 'root' user, therefore the NFS share needs to be mounted using the 'root' user and it needs to created with no-root-squash option in the backend store.
We will need some more changes to pass this case as well."}, {'account_id': 9190, 'date': '2014-09-23 18:51:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 9190, 'date': '2014-09-23 18:59:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Some questions/doubts with respect to this change, please help clarify:

In a typical deployment the backend storage would be configured with external LDAP/Active Directory for authenticating the data users. So in such setup, we need to have the 'stack' user, in whose context the Openstack services (cinder-volume for instance) would run, be part of the LDAP/AD. Do we consider this fact? And is this what is expected in this case? What happens if someone changes the stack user creds on LDAP/AD? the cinder volume service will start failing for many operations.

My queries might be quite naive, but please help me educate on this.

Thanks in advance."}, {'account_id': 9190, 'date': '2014-09-30 13:58:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Hi Nilesh,

The configuration of LDAP/AD is not required for this change and, in fact, my test environment has no "extra" NFS security environment set up other than ID mapping for NFSv4 and configuring the NFS server to squash root. This is the very basic configuration. More sophisticated security can be set up from there. And yes, the "stack" user should be configured at the NFS server and changing the user would impact access at the NFS server. This is expected of course as that is what having security is all about: verifying user access and authorization (RW privileges) rather than configuring everything with root level access.'}, {'account_id': 10628, 'date': '2014-09-30 14:01:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

I'm not familiar with this patch to make sense of the points that were raised in the #openstack-cinder channel. I will spend time over the weekend to do so."}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2014-10-13 00:34:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

(7 comments)

I'm fine with this going into the RemoteFS driver if it's optional as Eric mentioned for drivers to turn it on and useful for other drivers.

Glenn, I know you were not happy with this going around in circles, but I cannot find in the patch history where things were put originally in the RemoteFS driver, and then put into the NFSDriver after. In fact, the first time remotefs.py was touched was patch set 11, and it never had the shared code.

So with that in mind, we will not block the patch for optionally providing this to drivers and we will not block this patch for making these things available in RemoteFS driver. I have some thoughts on how this information should be made available to the drivers as well, which can be read in volume/manager.py, but I will also be bringing it up in the #openstack-cinder channel on Monday."}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:53:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: Code-Review-1

Just for the record, I'm still opposed from adding DB access to the drivers, for those cases where it may have crept in I'd propose it be removed.

This is fairly trivial to wrap and leave in the manager, even if you have to add a driver method that reports whether it supports it or not.

Default driver just returns False, Shares based drivers can return True, I honestly don't care if it's False 99% of the time."}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-10-14 19:45:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

> Just for the record, I'm still opposed from adding DB access to the drivers, for those cases where it may have crept in I'd propose it be removed.
So we don't confuse things -- the patchset here isn't doing that yet.

> This is fairly trivial to wrap and leave in the manager, even if you have to add a driver method that reports whether it supports it or not.

I'm not sure this is possible.  The path to set this at driver init time is when the driver is loaded with import_object() in VolumeManager's init.  You can't examine the driver to ask whether the driver supports/wants this at that time because it's already too late.  Trying to set it after the driver has initialized may cause a race condition, I'm not sure.

> Default driver just returns False, Shares based drivers can return True, I honestly don't care if it's False 99% of the time."}, {'account_id': 9190, 'date': '2014-10-15 16:00:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

(10 comments)

Okay, so let me summarize what the directions I am getting now.

1) No volume DB lookups in the driver.
    We will do the DB query in VolumeManager and pass the indicator to the driver(s) via kwargs.

2) The Volume driver code does file based operations (e.g., chown, run as root) so it must be known if the operation is to be done as secure or insecure. Rather than introducing "driver type" checking code in Volume, use a method call (self.is_running_in_secure_file_mode()) to determine if the driver does or does not support secure file operations. This may mean that many times the call is not necessary BUT it keeps driver type checking out of the Volume driver and any driver can call itself secure by overriding this method.
 
3) Move the functionality from the NFS driver down into the RemoteFS driver so that all Network Attached Storage systems will be able to use secure environments.

This is the indicated direction by the Core team and should not meet with -1 reviews.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-10-15 19:47:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

'}, {'created': '2014-08-06 19:53:43.000000000', 'message': 'NFS Security Enhancements: allows secure NFS environment setup.

This patch allows an OpenStack environment to run as a secure NFS
environment from the client and server perspective, including having
root squash enabled. This also sets Cinder file permissions as 660:
removing other/world file access, based upon a new config flag called
nfs_secure_files.

The "nfs_secure_files" option defaults to "autodetect" and is used
in upgrade versues new install scenarios. When "autodetect" is
observed during Cinder startup, a check is done to determine if there
are existing Cinder volumes: no volumes will use Secure NFS and
existing volumes will use current NFS security settings. The
Administrator may override the default "autodetect" with "True" or
"False".

Change-Id: I3d25f593beab7f5462576b14ab62d13d8c53e7c6
Implements: blueprint secure-nfs

'}, {'created': '2014-09-23 18:51:12.000000000', 'message': 'NFS Security Enhancements: allows secure NFS environment setup.

This patch allows an OpenStack environment to run as a secure NFS
environment from the client and server perspective, including having root
squash enabled and not running file based operations as the 'root' user. This
also sets Cinder file permissions as 660: removing other/world file access.

The "nfs_secure_files" option controls the setting of file permissions when
Cinder volumes are created. The option defaults to "auto" and is used in
upgrade versues new install scenarios. When "auto" is observed during Cinder
startup, a check is done to determine if there are existing Cinder volumes: no
volumes will set the option to 'true', use Secure NFS file permissions.
The detection of existing volumes will set the option to 'false', use the
current insecure file permissions setting. The Administrator may override the
default "auto" with "true" or "false".

The "nfs_secure_operations" option controls whether file based operations are
run as the 'root' user or the current OpenStack 'process' user. The option
The option defaults to "auto" and is used in upgrade versues new install
scenarios. When "auto" is observed during Cinder startup, a check is done to
determine if there are existing Cinder volumes: no volumes will set the option
to 'true', be secure and do NOT run as the 'root' user. The detection of
existing volumes will set the option to 'false', use the current method of
running operations as the 'root' user.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3d25f593beab7f5462576b14ab62d13d8c53e7c6
Implements: blueprint secure-nfs
Closes-Bug: 1260679

'}, {'created': '2014-10-08 17:36:12.000000000', 'message': 'NFS Security Enhancements: allows secure NFS environment setup.

This patch allows an OpenStack environment to run as a secure NFS
environment from the client and server perspective, including having
root squash enabled and not running file based operations as the
'root' user. This also sets Cinder file permissions as 660: removing
other/world file access. This patch is for NFS systems; RemoteFS
systems are not impacted but can easily be modified to use the NFS
security when desired.

The "nfs_secure_files" option controls the setting of file
permissions when Cinder volumes are created. The option defaults to
"auto" and is used in upgrade versues new install scenarios. When
"auto" is observed during Cinder startup, a check is done to
determine if there are existing Cinder volumes: no volumes will set
the option to 'true', use Secure NFS file permissions. The detection
of existing volumes will set the option to 'false', use the current
insecure file permissions setting. The Administrator may override the
default "auto" with "true" or "false".

The "nfs_secure_operations" option controls whether file based
operations are run as the 'root' user or the current OpenStack
'process' user. The option defaults to "auto" and is used in
upgrade versues new install scenarios. When "auto" is observed
during Cinder startup, a check is done to determine if there are
existing Cinder volumes: no volumes will set the option to 'true', be
secure and do NOT run as the 'root' user. The detection of existing
volumes will set the option to 'false', use the current method of
running operations as the 'root' user. For new installations, a
'marker file' is written so that subsequent restarts of Cinder
will know what the original determination had been.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3d25f593beab7f5462576b14ab62d13d8c53e7c6
Implements: blueprint secure-nfs
Closes-Bug: 1260679
'}, {'created': '2014-10-09 22:03:41.000000000', 'message': 'NFS Security Enhancements: allows secure NFS environment setup.

This patch allows an OpenStack environment to run as a secure NFS
environment from the client and server perspective, including having
root squash enabled and not running file based operations as the
'root' user. This also sets Cinder file permissions as 660: removing
other/world file access. This patch is for NFS systems; RemoteFS
systems are not impacted but can easily be modified to use the
Network File System security mode when desired.

The "secure_file_permissions" option controls the setting of file
permissions when Cinder volumes are created. The option defaults to
"auto" and is used in upgrade versues new install scenarios. When
"auto" is observed during Cinder startup, a check is done to
determine if there are existing Cinder volumes: no volumes will set
the option to 'true', use secure file permissions. The detection
of existing volumes will set the option to 'false', use the current
insecure file permissions setting. The Administrator may override the
default "auto" with "true" or "false".

The "secure_file_operations" option controls whether file based
operations are run as the 'root' user or the current OpenStack
'process' user. The option defaults to "auto" and is used in
upgrade versues new install scenarios. When "auto" is observed
during Cinder startup, a check is done to determine if there are
existing Cinder volumes: no volumes will set the option to 'true', be
secure and do NOT run as the 'root' user. The detection of existing
volumes will set the option to 'false', use the current method of
running operations as the 'root' user. For new installations, a
'marker file' is written so that subsequent restarts of Cinder
will know what the original determination had been.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3d25f593beab7f5462576b14ab62d13d8c53e7c6
Implements: blueprint secure-nfs
Closes-Bug: 1260679

functionality with the same config options.

commit_message:
NFS Security Enhancements: allows secure NFS environment setup

This patch allows an OpenStack environment to run as a secure NAS
environment from the client and server perspective, including having
root squash enabled and not running file operations as the 'root'
user. This also sets Cinder file permissions as 660: removing
other/world file access.

The "nas_secure_file_permissions" option controls the setting of file
permissions when Cinder volumes are created. The option defaults to
"auto" to gracefully handle upgrade scenarios. When set to "auto",
a check is done during Cinder startup to determine if there are
existing Cinder volumes: no volumes will set the option to 'true',
and use secure file permissions. The detection of existing volumes will
set the option to 'false', and use the current insecure method of
handling file permissions.

The "nas_secure_file_operations" option controls whether file
operations are run as the 'root' user or the current OpenStack
'process' user. The option defaults to "auto" to gracefully handle
upgrade scenarios. When set to "auto", a check is done during Cinder
startup to determine if there are existing Cinder volumes: no volumes
will set the option to 'true', be secure and do NOT run as the 'root'
user. The detection of existing volumes will set the option to 'false',
and use the current method of running operations as the 'root' user.
For new installations, a 'marker file' is written so that subsequent
restarts of Cinder will know what the original determination had been.

This patch enables this functionality only for the NFS driver.
Other similar drivers can use this code to enable the same
functionality with the same config options.

DocImpact
Change-Id: I3d25f593beab7f5462576b14ab62d13d8c53e7c6
Implements: blueprint secure-nfs
Partial-Bug: 1260679

Ghe, thanks for volunteering, this is very generous of you! :)'}, {'account_id': 9420, 'date': '2014-10-02 13:24:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

If we are going to remove guidelines that aren't currently adhered to, then we're back to square 1 with messy code and no guidelines at all."}, {'account_id': 9420, 'date': '2014-10-02 13:25:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Opps - forgot the -1 :)'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-10-02 14:21:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I had a chat with Matthew and I'd like to clarify my argument. I agree we have to be able to introduce new rules somehow. However the standard method of introducing a new rule includes three things:

 1. Document the rule
 2. Provide an automated check (EG in dib-lint)
 3. Clean up existing usage

In this case, #2 + #3 have not been provided. I feel bad enforcing the rule without #3 especially since it means the current code is no guide to correct practice, creating a snare for new contributors. It also suggests some hypocrisy between what we (incl. me) say is important and what we're willing to fix.

Finally there are two particularities in play: existing local vars are nigh-all capitalised and even minor inconsistency undermines the informational benefit of having the rule. These make a gradual introduction more troublesome than for proper quoting practices, for example.

If someone is willing to submit clean-up patches, I'll review them and we can keep the rule. Until then we shouldn't enforce this rule and hence we shouldn't document it."}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-10-07 02:01:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I agree with Alexis; introduction of a new rule should include making sure that tools like dib-lint can run cleanly over the existing code. Reviewers should not be expected to manually remember all the rules *and* manually parse whether each violation is new (and should be fixed) or existing (and should be left alone).'}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-10-07 02:05:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

On second thoughts: some of these variables are intended to feed config into the script from the environment. Re-casing them is a non-backwards-compatible change (unless we do some messy code to detect the mis-cased variable and re-case it). That makes it significantly non-trivial to modify existing code to follow this rule.

Taking this rule out would only make that problem worse over time.

In this case I think I'd prefer to keep the rule in."}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-10-07 09:39:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Hi James, on your specific feedback:

> some of these variables are intended to feed config into the script from the environment. Re-casing them is a non-backwards-compatible change.

The rule is (more or less) that purely script-internal variables are lowercase; all other variables are uppercase. This latter includes variables passed in, EG "to feed config into the script". 90-100% of these are already uppercase so no recasing is required.

Admittedly if we removed the rule and people suddenly started merging new vars in lowercase, it could get awkward. There's no reason to believe they would though; uppercase is generally preferred and the env-var-as-config pattern is discouraged now.'}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-10-08 21:10:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I started looking at some scripts  and now I'm more undecided.

For cases where a variable is being read to pull in data from the environment, I think it's actually fairly simple to handle the case where the internal variable has different spelling than the external:

INTERNAL_VARIABLE=${externalVariable:-12345}

If we want to deprecate that spelling and push for the external variable to be uppercase as well, that's still doable.:

INTERNAL_VARIABLE=${EXTERNAL_VARIABLE:-${externalVariable:-12345}}

will let us use the new spelling if it's set, but look for the old spelling if the new spelling isn't used.

So I don't think "backwards compatibility" is a concern.


... I do think it's a significant amount of work to retrofit this to our scripts though, and I do dislike having a rule we don't enforce.

I'd still like to keep it around for new code though, and to encourage our existing code to be improved.

I'm on the fence at the moment, but I think I'm leaning a little more towards keeping the rule even though our existing code does have violations.'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-10-09 09:42:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I'm worried that you showed external variables in lowercase and internal variables in uppercase, which is precisely the opposite of what the rule states. Does this information change your thinking at all?

For example, since external vars are already upper case, which they should be according to the rule, we don't need to apply any back-compat hacks. Unless someone goes on a mad lower-casing spree, which could be prevented by changing the rule to "All TripleO variables should be upper case". This would be closest to what we've been following in practice.

I don't think the rule is useful unless we can rely on it being adhered to, so there's no point applying it only to new code. There's also EG "no_proxy" - an external variable which violates the rule. This shows we can never wholly rely on the rule (unless we add an exceptions list for everyone to memorise).'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-10-24 12:05:16.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Giving up'}]

commit_message:
Remove variable case requirement

Although the requirement disambiguates exported from non-exported vars,
which is useful, few if any of our existing scripts apply it. This makes
it difficult to enforce on new commits. I'd rather not have HACKING
rules which are unenforced.

I'd not object to this being reintroduced along with a cleanup to
existing scripts. I do think that'll be impractical but if someone feels
strongly they're welcome to do the work.

Change-Id: Iafde3c94caeb81f5daf0b97bffc61155fcadee76

commit_message:
Fix CLI cron-trigger tests

Field 'Workflow Input' was removed because of problem with passing
passwords through CLI (passwords have to be hide).

That's why checks for this field were removed from tests.

I'm with Lucas in that I don't understand how this helps much.  We create the token file in the driver's deploy() just before powering it on.  It sounds like the issue is that server POST + boot is longer than the token expiry, but with this change we only refresh the token if the time it took for the deploy task to be created and acted upon bumps bumps the token to expire "soon."  I'd rather see this handled as part of a periodic task that refreshes on-disk tokens as required for nodes in DEPLOY_WAIT, or document that operators need to configure keystone with a longer token expiry for slow servers.'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2014-10-08 08:10:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Hi Yuriy,

@Dmitry, I don't really think it needs a spec, the bug is fine but need some more explanation.

As @Adam describe I just don't see how it works, I understand that a machine may delay to boot up and the token may expire in the mean time, but we don't have anything that keeps updating the token, so does that means that the token sent with the deploy request may be already about to expire? Is that it?"}, {'account_id': 7711, 'date': '2014-10-15 13:41:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Lucas, yes it is right. commit_message:
Get new auth token for ramdisk if old will expire soon

PXE driver prepares auth token for ramdisk, if this token near
expiration deploy will be fail. This patch modify PXE driver,
get new token from Keystone for this case. New function
token_expires_soon() added to keystone module.

Closes-Bug: #1377168
Change-Id: I215e2ec679b510152e2d140234594f7596e602af

commit_message:
set close_fds=True in Popen

The current way of using Popen does not close pipes properly,
and therefore long-running keystone processes, which depends on
keystoneclient.common.cms for data sigining, eventually hit
open file limit and stop working. Passing close_fds=True seems
to have solved the problem.

Change-Id: Ife452ab6843c1af5eb39debb8db453e45f78cba9
Closes-Bug: 1382906

commit_message:
Rename config => system-config in devstack-gate

The openstack-infra/config repo has been renamed to
openstack-infra/system-config. This patch edits devstack-gate
doc file.

Change-Id: I55eaf754f43be8fe273e8d4d591d18b73880a913

commit_message:
Create 'quota' table in folsom_initial

When using the stable icehouse branch
folsom_initial db migration does not create quotas table
for a plugin which had db quota support (quota-ext).

This bug was fixed as part of bug 1207402 in master.
Since this bug cannot be back ported, we back port only
the quota table related fix.

Closes-bug: #1372678

Change-Id: I933aaefb50e32234eaad5557322e4c89af2a47d0

commit_message:
Retry on closing of luks encrypted volume in case device is busy

We're seeing races in the gate on detach of an encrypted volume where
the device is busy so the detach fails, which causes the delete of the
volume on the cinder side to fail because the volume is still in use and
then Tempest times out waiting for the volume to be deleted.

This simply adds a retry to close the encryption device.  I use
attempts=3 since that's what we use for lvremove.

Closes-Bug: #1374458

Change-Id: Ia0667da7dee247ba8c3338b296244b2a71d1045d

commit_message:
Set owner+group from control file

Add keys 'uid' and 'gid' to control file. The values may be UID/GIDs or
names. In either case, the value is checked against the passwd/group
database to ensure it exists.

Change-Id: I1730a126cf024755635043b1a0f70006ab22c046

quoting from a review left on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/73738/ (a previous incarnation of this patch with other good comments and history)

----

I was recently in a situation in which I needed to package swift.
The project I am working on does not currently require or use other openstack components, but does require some extra middleware for swift:
https://github.com/zerovm/zerocloud
We're also carrying some minor patches as we work on getting some of the changes that optimize swift for our use cases into upstream swift.
Normally, packaging python applications is a breeze. We're running ubuntu, and debhelper has some great helpers for distutils. Most things just work. We'd packaged swift prior to the shift to pbr, and this went quite well.
With pbr, though, life became significantly more complicated.
We now needed python-pbr, so we tried to build it, only to discover that it also had additional build requirements.
Build-Depends: debhelper (>= 9), openstack-pkg-tools, python-all (>= 2.6.6-3~), python-coverage, python-d2to1 (>= 0.2.10), python-fixtures, python-setuptools, python-sphinx, python-subunit, python-testrepository (>= 0.0.14), python-testresources, python-testtools, python3-all, python3-d2to1 (>= 0.2.10), python3-setuptools, subunit
Once we worked our way through packaging these things, we discovered that in its default configuration, pbr will trigger sphinx to auto generate documentation, pulling information from git. This doesn't work too well on a typical package build server.
I fully understand why some of this functionality is useful, but when it comes to performing normal system administration tasks like packaging projects, pbr definitely doesn't provide much assistance -- it takes a great deal of work to build a package.
Having a normal distutils setup.py in addition to a setup.cfg will definitely help out packagers and still let users take advantage of some of the doc generation and testing facilities provided by pbr.
Thanks so much for writing this patch!"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-07 19:20:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: No score

commit_message:
Make PBR based setup completely optional

 * Tradtional setup.py is available as pkg_setup.py
 * PBR based setup.py is avaialble as pbr_setup.py

If you run setup.py with pbr installed you get pbr_setup.py otherwise,
just regular setuptools (default).

You can also choose to use either xxx_setup.py file explicitly (i.e.
never use pbr based setup even if it's installed, or use pbr based
setup where pbr is installed at build time)

Change-Id: Ifcd64c35abd1fae1c72909d5b724b36020a0c698

commit_message:
fuel_upgrade: add ability to use diff-based repo

In Fuel 6.0 we're going to introduce diff-based releases, so the
fuel-upgrade script has to handle and install it properly.

Change-Id: If05ac74b680691bf9adb54caf8958e235ec767ef

can't connect to mirrors.fedoraproject.org over https

---
[root@test ~]# urlgrabber -d 1,debug.txt https://mirrors.fedoraproject.org/metalink?repo=epel-6
* About to connect() to mirrors.fedoraproject.org port 443 (#0)
*   Trying 140.211.169.197... * connected
* Connected to mirrors.fedoraproject.org (140.211.169.197) port 443 (#0)
* Initializing NSS with certpath: sql:/etc/pki/nssdb
*   CAfile: /etc/pki/tls/certs/ca-bundle.crt
  CApath: none
* NSS error -8092
* Closing connection #0
* SSL connect error
---

This requires an update of ca-certificates before it will work.

Change-Id: I9c5e595aa2b8e86188cb7db658ce4b630e6d0774
'}]
commit_message:
Update ca-certificates for HP Cloud centos6 images

The current HP cloud official centos6 images ("CentOS 6.3 Server
64-bit 20130116" - c1f9f404-39c2-4e83-b4bb-90d5ead16a36) by default
can't connect to mirrors.fedoraproject.org over https

---
[root@test ~]# urlgrabber -d 1,debug.txt https://mirrors.fedoraproject.org/metalink?repo=epel-6
* About to connect() to mirrors.fedoraproject.org port 443 (#0)
*   Trying 140.211.169.197... * connected
* Connected to mirrors.fedoraproject.org (140.211.169.197) port 443 (#0)
* Initializing NSS with certpath: sql:/etc/pki/nssdb
*   CAfile: /etc/pki/tls/certs/ca-bundle.crt
  CApath: none
* NSS error -8092
* Closing connection #0
* SSL connect error
---

This requires an update of ca-certificates before it will work.

Change-Id: I9c5e595aa2b8e86188cb7db658ce4b630e6d0774

commit_message:
Allow extraction of list items

OAC can be used to get a key from metadata by supplying EG '--key A'.
You can also extract an item from a dict, EG '--key A.B'.
However, if A is a list, there's no way to get an item out of the list.

Extend the expression language (if that's not too grand a term) to
support this. EG '--key A.0' gets the first item out of the list A.
'--key A.1.B' gets B out of the second item of list A (which must be a
dict).

Change-Id: I406cbd2d974544ed5948e137359629184d8ee156

commit_message:
Replace get_default_image_service usage.

There are get_default_image_service usages in compute layer, this
patch replace them with image.api functions.

Change-Id: I9f3aaa3e81c30a2a4d62791fafd3117eaf6994bd

commit_message:
Added Event Logs to Sahara

* Added DB models
* Added required alembic migrations
* Added method which can assign event to cluster
* Added method which can provide abibility to get events from REST API
* Added simple usage: events about cluster status changing

TODO:

* Add another usages (will be added as separate CR to avoid rebasing)
* Docs needs to be updated (will be added as separate CR)
* Tests required

Implements blueprint: event-log
Change-Id: Idde32eb58317d382d52381131b80c9a138596fec

[{'created': '2014-10-22 20:57:54.000000000', 'message': 'Add jobs to api-wg repo

The intent of this patch is to do the following:

  - set up a check and gate job for py27 and docs
  - if merged successfully, then publish the docs to:

commit_message:
Add jobs to api-wg repo

The intent of this patch is to do the following:

  - set up a check and gate job for py27 and docs
  - if merged successfully, then publish the docs to:
    specs.o.org/openstack/api-wg

Change-Id: I52dd86899c175c28999a338fa51cd8c8133d0430

[{'created': '2014-09-29 17:18:12.000000000', 'message': "Fix CellStateManagerFile init to failure

Currently, specifying a cells_config file in nova.conf causes
CellStateManager to fail and in turn stops the nova-cells service from
starting. The reason is that CellsManager creates an instance of
CellStateManager with no arguments. CellStateManager __new__ runs and
creates an instance of CellStateManagerFile which runs __new__ and
__init__ with cell_state_cls and cells_config_path set. At this point
__new__ returns CellStateManagerFile and the new instance's __init__
method is invoked (CellStateManagerFile.__init__) with the original
arguments (there weren't any) which then results in:
2014-04-29 11:52:05.240 16759 TRACE nova self.state_manager =
cell_state_manager()
2014-04-29 11:52:05.240 16759 TRACE nova TypeError: __init__() takes
exactly 3 arguments (1 given)

It seems reasonable for CellStateManagerFile to derive the
cells_config_path info for itself so I have updated the code with that
change and added unit tests to catch this bug and to check that the
correct managers are still returned

Change-Id: I9021640515142a3ca95c2d9e7b03e19b529bc175
Closes-Bug: #1314677

commit_message:
Fix CellStateManagerFile init to failure

Currently, specifying a cells_config file in nova.conf causes
CellStateManager to fail and in turn stops the nova-cells service from
starting. The reason is that CellsManager creates an instance of
CellStateManager with no arguments. CellStateManager __new__ runs and
creates an instance of CellStateManagerFile which runs __new__ and
__init__ with cell_state_cls and cells_config_path set. At this point
__new__ returns CellStateManagerFile and the new instance's __init__
method is invoked (CellStateManagerFile.__init__) with the original
arguments (there weren't any) which then results in:
2014-04-29 11:52:05.240 16759 TRACE nova self.state_manager =
cell_state_manager()
2014-04-29 11:52:05.240 16759 TRACE nova TypeError: __init__() takes
exactly 3 arguments (1 given)

It seems reasonable for CellStateManagerFile to derive the
cells_config_path info for itself so I have updated the code with that
change and added unit tests to catch this bug and to check that the
correct managers are still returned

Closes-Bug: #1314677
(cherry picked from commit 695191fa89387d96e60120ff32965493c844e7f5)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/cells/test_cells_state_manager.py

Change-Id: I9021640515142a3ca95c2d9e7b03e19b529bc175

commit_message:
Make rdo-release install safe

Like the epel element, this may be applied to a system that already
has rdo-release installed.  If that happens yum exits non-zero
because for some reason it considers "nothing to do" to be an error.

This simply checks for the existence of the rdo-release rpm before
attempting to install it.

Change-Id: I5867ca074cc1afa843ef1e0f85c1c9b6f2deb403

commit_message:
Add a new openstack-specs repo under the control of the TC

One of the takeaways from the exercise about kilo priorities was oslo is
not the right home for all cross project discussions. We need a new home
for cross project specs, and since the TC is our governing technical
committee this repo should be under their management.

Change-Id: Id9393dfc2c7f1f883a5f20d85f7ecb79e2c52063

commit_message:
Fix resource leakage in messaging.test_queues

Test messaging.test_queues.test_delete_queue does pop 1 element from
shared list (self.queues which is being used by other tests as well
as in resource cleanup) and then delete request is done.

In case where delete request fails then it cause other tests to fail
and resource leakage as element has been removed from self.queues
even before actual deletion.

Individual test should not be side-effecting mutable class variables
that are used by other tests. So merging delete tests with create tests.

Closes-Bug: #1377031

Change-Id: If24a903160e716a685d7121e0968881542f072fc

commit_message:
Handle extra spaces in merge-svc-map-files

During internal testing we are getting the following error from
merge-svc-map-files
File "/tmp/image.K2MYCphY/hooks/extra-data.d/10-merge-svc-map-files", line 54, in main
    with open(data_path, 'r') as dataFile:
IOError: [Errno 21] Is a directory: '...diskimage-builder/elements/svc-map'

Somehow IMAGE_ELEMENT contains a extra white space that manifests itself
as an element without a name. It is very hard to find where this is coming from so
instead this patch makes merge-svc-map-files more robost to this situation

Change-Id: Id1500ead8a77d691408617dcdc4e095bc5775be8

commit_message:
Add block completion signal

In I973d197245ed32612bde9209479e6ae3a443fc69, the signal_transport was
set to NO_SIGNAL to prevent the resource staying CREATE_IN_PROGRESS
forever. This means that Heat reports the stack is configured before it
actually is.

The correct fix was to add completion-signal to BlockStorageConfig.
However now there's a BlockStorage0AllNodesDeployment, we simply have to
receive the signal from allNodesConfig by setting the deployment
signal-transport.

Change-Id: I1f6408ca39fddd146e7aae140f61d265bbf563ec

@liusheng, I don't think eglynn's alternative in patch set 1 requires having compute-agent listening on the notification bus. You can have the libvirt inspector register callback functions for certain events from the underlying hypervisor, just like what nova does in https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py#L671"}, {'account_id': 8290, 'date': '2014-08-01 03:32:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Lianhao Lu, thanks for your suggestion ,that is a good idea, you mean add hook for virt-layer events, but there is a problem: in current implementation of Nova, when we update/set/delete a instance's metadata, the libvirt driver will do nothing, just update the instance info in db.

Or maybe we can add hook for notifications when collector receive and handle the notifications about instances. in the hook method, collector send a RPC call to compute-agent to notify the instance info(nova part) has been updated, and then compute-agent will re-get the instance info by nova API . what do you think about this?"}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2014-08-01 05:12:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@liusheng, I think we need to figure out the following questions before jumping into your resend notification method:

1. In what cases that a nova VM's metadata is changed, the the libvirt level registered callback can NOT detect that. 
2. In those cases, does that change in metadata could be detected through notification event?"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-20 19:52:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

commit_message:
Improve nfs-server to support multiple shares and options

With this we aim at making the nfs-server element capable of
deploying an arbitrary number of shares and to define for each
a list of clients allowed and the respective export options.

Change-Id: Ib056885c94c3bc475ed0e84237c83414795fc8e0

Adding SNMP related parameters to storage templates

These SNMP parameters are needed for monitoring using Ceilometer.
Also fixing bad defaults.

commit_message:
Update use of open() in object API

* Switch to use io.open() for py3 compatibility and simpler testing.
* Open files in 'rb' mode to avoid translation on Windows

Previously tests simply relied on files that were present in the
repository to run tests using open().  Change the filenames to ensure
that no longer happens.

requests_mock doesn't have a way to match against the request body for
PUT/POST; an attempt to add a new Matcher to do that worked but it
needs to subclass the currently private adapter._Matcher class or
duplicate most of its functionality.

Change-Id: I8c30b41db20af8ecafe67e760e872fc08adec905

Remove pip install --pre

We were installing some packages with support for prerelease versions in
expectation of needing it in our CI. This turns out to not be needed so
we should remove it.

commit_message:
Add config option for XML support in Networking

The first step to removing XML in Kilo is making XML testing optional.
Stable test configs will need to be updated to enable this feature to prevent
regressions in stable releases.

Change-Id: I30b9565e01c623814a9c503c4b1c26642afed878

commit_message:
Add maintenance to RESTful web API documentation

This adds [PUT|DELETE] v1/nodes/(node_uuid)/maintenance
to our RESTful web API documentation. It will show up at

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/ironic/webapi/v1.html#nodes

Change-Id: I42171e429ec72d270b51b246d7c8c6c38fed2e1e
Implements: blueprint maintenance-reason

commit_message:
Update HP 3PAR supported operations

Manage/unmanage support was added in the Juno release with patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113729/

This patch is adding the manage and unmanage a volume to the list
of supported operations for the HP 3PAR drivers.

Change-Id: I00aba2b753fa9655031ee49f7ad823b9e6e573a4

commit_message:
Convert all HTML doc to RST

The motivation for this conversion is to have DevStack's docs be
generated using a more familair workflow for OpenStack projects, using
Sphinx.

Changing from raw HTML to RST will also make it easier to contribute
more documentation, as well as making edits less of a hassle.

The majority of the work was done by using Pandoc to convert from HTML
to RST, with minor edits to the output to remove errors in Sphinx.

Change-Id: I9636017965aeade37b950ddf5bdb0c22ab9004bd

[{'created': '2014-10-23 11:59:32.000000000', 'message': "Correct CA cert argument for glanceclient

Heat need to pass the CA cert to glanceclient to load image data
during stack creation when glance api is configured with SSL.
Currently the client is passing the wrong cert key to glanceclient.
The key should be 'cacert' instead of 'ca_file'.

Change-Id: Ie542dda1354776e62507240c917c1cffbc222f17
Closes-Bug: #1384626
"}]
commit_message:
Correct CA cert argument for glanceclient

Heat need to pass the CA cert to glanceclient to load image data
during stack creation when glance api is configured with SSL.
Currently the client is passing the wrong cert key to glanceclient.
The key should be 'cacert' instead of 'ca_file'.

Change-Id: Ie542dda1354776e62507240c917c1cffbc222f17
Closes-Bug: #1384626

commit_message:
Save test output of run_tests.sh to textfile

Using tee to save the rest output of run_tests.sh.
It is helpful to locate the failure you concerned when there are
lots of failures. And use don't need to redirect the output from
command line.

It is also aligned with the consequence code: "cat run_tests.log".

Bug #1219690

Change-Id: I868c0fc72e4139470956929668db337ca63f0155

commit_message:
Move unit tests from test_backend_ldap

There were a couple of unit tests in test_backend_ldap for
functions in keystone.common.ldap. Unit tests should be in
keystone.tests.unit.common.test_ldap because they don't need to
run multiple times for different configurations of the ldap
backend.

Change-Id: Ifcfd2c5610eb6870e6876af671a3fbdd779c659b

[{'created': '2014-09-09 09:28:37.000000000', 'message': "PKI and PKIZ tokens unnecessary whitespace removed

In the race to produce smaller PKI tokens, we've overlooked
that we can produce smaller JSON bodies by removing all whitespace
between structural characters.

This patch offers a solution by overloading
item_separator and key_separator in class SmarterEncoder
used to produce json response.

Change-Id: Id7fcc82a28359e85feac57f9469f2bcd9192ee50

commit_message:
PKI and PKIZ tokens unnecessary whitespace removed

In the race to produce smaller PKI tokens, we've overlooked
that we can produce smaller JSON bodies by removing all whitespace
between structural characters.

This patch offers a solution by overloading
item_separator and key_separator in class SmarterEncoder
used to produce json response.

Change-Id: Id7fcc82a28359e85feac57f9469f2bcd9192ee50
Closes-Bug: #1348262

commit_message:
sync oslo-incubator for request_id shim

Sync 838a2a3 oslo-incubator to get the new request_id shim, so
can introduce a deprecation warning that tells operators upgrading
from Juno that their paste.ini files need to point to oslo.middleware

This also syncs all other modules, except policy, which looks like it
needs some changes to heat thus will be handled via another patch.

Note we shouldn't remove this request_id shim until after Kilo is
branched.

Change-Id: I35125ffa263b0522ff6dd0b80b0beb3cbc79999b
Related-Bug: #1380629

commit_message:
Make sure the --heat-url option is respected

If the endpoint is passed in, make sure keystone uses it instead of
looking up the endpoint in the auth plugin.

Change-Id: I1c1c21d9533cd78f2dbfac91dcf0c6e9702b7c88
Closes-Bug: #1379933

Fix security groups

Security groups are now hanlded correctly for both Nova Network and
Neutron while using direct provisioning engine.

Change-Id: Id144d6559c4fbdfede59777382d9903bd1bab0cf
Closes-Bug: #1381035

commit_message:
Move to download.fedoraproject.org

download.fedoraproject.org is the mirror system, while
dl.fedoraproject.org is just one system. We have seen performance issues
with dl.fedoraproject.org and using download.fedoraproject.org was a
recommended as a solution by the folks at #fedora-admin.

Local testing on a rackspace server with dl.fedoraproject.org got about
70K/s while download.fedoraproject.org got over 1M/s

Move over to https as well.

Related-Bug: #1383928
Change-Id: I318d8844cfcfbc42c1e552e443c6b793d20f321f

commit_message:
Add selection of Django session engine to this module

This allows Django to be set to use something other than
the default session engine through Puppet. By default,
it will have no impact on existing configurations.

We've added this because our security constraints make signed cookies
as a session store for Horizon undesirable. The reasons for this are:

  * Sessions become vulnerable to replay attacks,
    a clean log-out is difficult to achieve.
  * Serializing sessions in cookies may allow an attacker
    to escalate read-only access to server configuration
    into code execution via deserialization of attacker-generated
    content.

Change-Id: Iaf80bdc1bb9ce55ff46b2dcfac73daad90fd0d37

commit_message:
VMware: Speed up transfer of images

The current implementation of the image transfer from Glance to
vCenter server is not as fast as it should be.
It is almost two times slower than "glance image-download | curl PUT".
The extra overhead comes from the copies of the bits from the
reading-thread to the queue and from the queue to the writing-thread.

This patch addresses the issue by removing the queue which doesn't
seem to have a valid reason to be there.

Fetch image (from Glance to VC):
1.5GB file: before 4m08s - now 2m30s

Snapshot (from VC to Glance):
1GB file: before: 3m56s - now 1m30s

Change-Id: Ifa2bdcc84d9e4d8668a9a346d9e050f2ac584048
Closes-Bug: #1278690

commit_message:
Storage planning info

Moved info from ref-arch to planning guide
- renamed file to 0100-storage-for images
  & subject to "Storage for Images"
- restructured information to read like planning issues
- removed list of Ceph limitations fixed in MOSt but not vanilla
  OpenStack -- they are moved to the ref-arch Ceph section
- now includes ephemeral as well as persistent storage;
  not a lot to say about ephemeral

terminology:  add ephemeral storage, lvm, persistent storage

user-guide:
- fix xref to planning material in configure/3500-cinder-glance-backend
- add tag to NTP section in initialize/400-pxe
- add config/settings/qcow to show the choice between qcow and raw
- added note to Settings/storage about selecting ephemeral storage

Closes-Bug: 1375823

Change-Id: I264e5c5fedac696e92d027b5e500b21dd74fb47e

commit_message:
Add [ssl] and 2 cinder attributes to nova.conf

This commit adds [ssl] section to nova.conf, which is used
to communicate with Glance when using https. It also adds
cinder_ca_certificates_file and cinder_api_insecure which are
needed for communicating with Cinder.

Change-Id: Id07f163dc7481ec26d0a5f8f1afb50e327318517
Closes-Bug: #1384118

Add ResourceGroup attribute example for all values

for an attribute of the resource in the group.  Related
to a question asked on IRC recently.

commit_message:
Add support for vhd vmdk vdi iso raw disk formats

Image upload provider already has a image type, but was not
used to handle the other common image types that have a simple
bare container format.   Expanded the list of types and allowed
the existing upload_image recipe to also take advantage of this
new provider disk type support in an optional way.  Backward
compatible.

Change-Id: I1f5983150aa648837c9bcd256f0ceb4bf73d4b52
Closes-Bug: #1383079

commit_message:
Extend some docstrings with useful information

This patch extends some of the docstrings in the `Client` class with
more useful information. The patch also adds `intersphinx` to allow for
linking to other docs within zaqarclient. For example:

    :rtype: :class:`zaqarclient.transport.base.Transport`

will link to the documentation for Transport if it has been generated.

Change-Id: I928d63d74739e9e18709979e79c95b5606d97032

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-09 21:23:05.000000000', 'message': "Move default stress test to run things 3 times instead of time based

Make the default setup for stress tests, what is run by 'tox -estress',
run all the jobs 3 times. The previous default was to run things for an
entire hour, which when factoring in devstack setup time would be one of
the longest things if we ran this in the check queue.

We want to run 'tox -estress' in the check queue as a sanity check of
the stress tests to make sure they are not code-rotting.

Change-Id: I90b4ec607b2e8ae55019c2e5153ba9533aef5f45
"}, {'created': '2014-10-09 21:46:45.000000000', 'message': "Add new tox target to sanity check stress tests

We want to run 'tox -estress-sanity' in the check queue as a sanity check of
the stress tests to make sure they work. This isn't supposed to be a
real stress test, just make sure the stress tests themselves work.

Change-Id: I90b4ec607b2e8ae55019c2e5153ba9533aef5f45
"}]
commit_message:
Add new tox target to sanity check stress tests

We want to run 'tox -estress-sanity' in the check queue as a sanity check of
the stress tests to make sure they work. This isn't supposed to be a
real stress test, just make sure the stress tests themselves work.

Change-Id: I90b4ec607b2e8ae55019c2e5153ba9533aef5f45

commit_message:
Support building wheels (PEP-427)

Universal is used to identify pure-Python module(by bdist_wheel). For
these, it is sufficient to build a wheel with _any_ Python ABI version
and publish that to PyPI (by whatever means).

Change-Id: Ied9e2aa765fe006d66df7f431462252204dc5baa

[{'created': '2014-10-23 19:39:25.000000000', 'message': 'Remove explicit set of CONF.os_region_name in mapr plugin tests

The explicit set of os_region_name to None breaks subsequent
unit tests running in the same worker process that attempt to
override os_region_name.  Any setting of os_region_name in unit
tests should use the set_override or set_default methods available
in oslo.config.

Close-bug: 1384875
Change-Id: Iea2eb58dc3d8e8667795495c6cc1f68538d524b6
'}]
commit_message:
Remove explicit set of CONF.os_region_name in mapr plugin tests

The explicit set of os_region_name to None breaks subsequent
unit tests running in the same worker process that attempt to
override os_region_name.  Any setting of os_region_name in unit
tests should use the set_override or set_default methods available
in oslo.config.

Close-bug: 1384875
Change-Id: Iea2eb58dc3d8e8667795495c6cc1f68538d524b6

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-21 03:58:29.000000000', 'message': "mask keystone token in debug output

replaying the keystone token in debug output is both completely
burdensome to read (given it's unbounded size), but it's also
potentially a security issue given that it could be used in replay
attacks.
Instead, filter the headers to sha1 sensitive things, with X-Auth-Token
being the only one listed so far. The sha1 will at least give us the
understanding of tokens being the same or different (and an administrator
could use that to figure out if they were valid later).
This also removes some extra '\n' that were being injected into the
debug logs, because they were not helping with readability.
Lastly, actually test logging. This introduces the first tests of the
logging path using the logging fixture. It's pretty basic, but does
verify that requests are logged at debug, that the SHA1 format works,
and that headers which are not listed get shown straight through.
DocImpact because this changes the curl dumped strings which people
may have been using. They can still do that as long as they generate
their own keystone token.

Ported from original change id:
I1edb94785705c3b6a05f118b77d3aeb07461cd44

Change-Id: Ie074e44bffac5e0f35d2162570fdba233b27dd0a
"}, {'created': '2014-09-21 12:59:46.000000000', 'message': "mask keystone token in debug output

commit_message:
Mask keystone token in debug output

replaying the keystone token in debug output is both completely
burdensome to read (given it's unbounded size), but it's also
potentially a security issue given that it could be used in replay
attacks.
Instead, filter the headers to sha1 sensitive things, with X-Auth-Token
being the only one listed so far. The sha1 will at least give us the
understanding of tokens being the same or different (and an administrator
could use that to figure out if they were valid later).
This also removes some extra '\n' that were being injected into the
debug logs, because they were not helping with readability.
Lastly, actually test logging. This introduces the first tests of the
logging path using the logging fixture. It's pretty basic, but does
verify that requests are logged at debug, that the SHA1 format works,
and that headers which are not listed get shown straight through.
DocImpact because this changes the curl dumped strings which people
may have been using. They can still do that as long as they generate
their own keystone token.

Ported from original change id:
I1edb94785705c3b6a05f118b77d3aeb07461cd44

Change-Id: Ie074e44bffac5e0f35d2162570fdba233b27dd0a

commit_message:
Add docs for `Client` instances

This patch documents the basic usage of `Client` instances. It does not
provide a detailed documentation about the methods exposed but a high
level documentation of what the recommended way to access these
resources is.

The current version refers to sections like 'core API', 'config' and
others that haven't been documented yet. Once they will be, proper links
to those sections will be added here.

Change-Id: I705498b8e4c19c75c9697419d1fd90c9a9ae40b9

commit_message:
Big Switch: Switch to TLSv1 in server manager

Switch to TLSv1 for the connections to the backend
controllers. The default SSLv3 is no longer considered
secure.

TLSv1 was chosen over .1 or .2 because the .1 and .2 weren't
added until python 2.7.9 so TLSv1 is the only compatible option
for py26.

Closes-Bug: #1384487
Change-Id: I68bd72fc4d90a102003d9ce48c47a4a6a3dd6e03

commit_message:
Setup developer docs for zaqarclient

Zaqar's client library is lacking of any kind of documentation. This
needs to be fixed, hence this patch. The patch adds the docs'
infrastructure to start writing the required documentation for the
library.

Change-Id: Ife171e352da4ec977202efcb3f1dcf573edcdc27

commit_message:
Repair tox -ecover

Some tests are ignored during the invocation of 'tox -epy27' and
similar, but they were not ignored during the 'cover' profile. Becuase
the ignored tests actually fail when run this means that 'tox -ecover'
could not be used.

This patch just ignores the same tests in the 'cover' profile as the
default.

Change-Id: I7952c312addfed87f6055c1a360adfbf1fd5b168
