commit_message:
Move to download.fedoraproject.org

download.fedoraproject.org is the mirror system, while
dl.fedoraproject.org is just one system. We have seen performance issues
with dl.fedoraproject.org and using download.fedoraproject.org was a
recommended as a solution by the folks at #fedora-admin.

Local testing on a rackspace server with dl.fedoraproject.org got about
70K/s while download.fedoraproject.org got over 1M/s

Move over to https as well.

Related-Bug: #1383928
Change-Id: I318d8844cfcfbc42c1e552e443c6b793d20f321f
(cherry picked from commit cac1317676dcb0efa489dd667793cf4f6b366170)

commit_message:
Remove icehouse heat slow job from tempest check

This commit removes the stable heat slow job from the tempest check
queue. This jobs were added originally to ensure branchless tempest
continued to work against the stable branches in all gating configs.
But, because of some heat bugs and changes in testing methodology this
job doesn't add much value for icehouse. That coupled with the recent
nodepool image cache issues we've been hitting it makes more sense to
just remove the job. If the value of the job is increased and after
nodepool issues are sorted we can add this back.

Change-Id: I88b61b6aa70a1e336aeff66560134d7444f91880

commit_message:
Ensure ofagent unit tests handles random hashseeds

Several tests in test_ofa_neutron_agent.py and test_ofa_flows.py fail when
running the unit tests with hashseed 2701526934.

This patch fixes the failing unit tests by specifying that assert_has_calls does
not need to assert any order.

Change-Id: I48d6601130f7de1f6eeb7333a17eddd82e7acbdf
Partial-Bug: 1348818

download.fedoraproject.org is the mirror system, while
dl.fedoraproject.org is just one system. We have seen performance issues
with dl.fedoraproject.org and using download.fedoraproject.org was a
recommended as a solution by the folks at #fedora-admin.
Local testing on a rackspace server with dl.fedoraproject.org got about
70K/s while download.fedoraproject.org got over 1M/s

Note this is not a cherry-pick of I318d8844cfcfbc42c1e552e443c6b793d20f321f, because that wouldn't work

Change-Id: Ic68efcef0ed62f7867114d6992aee1610d6e8eb9
Related-Bug: #1383928
"}]
commit_message:
Move to download.fedoraproject.org

download.fedoraproject.org is the mirror system, while
dl.fedoraproject.org is just one system. We have seen performance issues
with dl.fedoraproject.org and using download.fedoraproject.org was a
recommended as a solution by the folks at #fedora-admin.
Local testing on a rackspace server with dl.fedoraproject.org got about
70K/s while download.fedoraproject.org got over 1M/s

Note this is not a cherry-pick of I318d8844cfcfbc42c1e552e443c6b793d20f321f, because that wouldn't work

Change-Id: Ic68efcef0ed62f7867114d6992aee1610d6e8eb9
Related-Bug: #1383928

Hi Dan

The previous commit that consolidated datastores changed the generic logic of datastore selection. This logic was to be used by both vmops.spawn & HostState.update_status.

Since we reverted the commit, we lost the changes to the datastore selection like checking the name against a regex and the accessibility of the datastore. We would like to retain them.

commit_message:
VMware: Restore datastore refactoring changes

A previous commit 9adba6727bbec051c1437ee95367ecb97b207f35 was
reverted because the driver reported aggregate disk stats.

This patch restores partial changes that refactored datastore
utility methods in that commit.

Change-Id: I4eee7d0478f8e25c60e008798e9db940565cd27a

commit_message:
Removed already configured steps in Debian

Many of the configuration directives which have to be manually
changed to follow the install-guide have been made the default
in Debian, therefore, it is preferable to simply remove them
from the install-guide, to make it easier for the end user.

Change-Id: Ib5babda7601e040f4b544e3b01e08b5b7f02cbc3

commit_message:
Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

Since puppet 3.x, Puppet Labs Forge accept only the metadata.json file
for module description (Modulefile is now deprecated).

This patch :
 - convert the Modulefile to metadata.json.
 - bump major version to 5 (for juno), and deps.
 - switch to stackforge namespace.
 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

Change-Id: I6aae75b5c2128f80e880bb4934811931db32eb59

subject: Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

commit_message:
Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

Since puppet 3.x, Puppet Labs Forge accept only the metadata.json file
for module description (Modulefile is now deprecated).

This patch :
 - convert the Modulefile to metadata.json.
 - bump major version to 5 (for juno), and deps.
 - switch to stackforge namespace.
 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

Change-Id: I173b13fe1ab32a3e32cc1581455333bea1eddf6d

subject: Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

Since puppet 3.x, Puppet Labs Forge accept only the metadata.json file
for module description (Modulefile is now deprecated).

This patch :
 - convert the Modulefile to metadata.json.
 - bump major version to 5 (for juno), and deps.
 - switch to stackforge namespace.
 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

Change-Id: Ie64090dd0adc112a40c5f1b47442578216afd5e4

 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

commit_message:
Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

Since puppet 3.x, Puppet Labs Forge accept only the metadata.json file
for module description (Modulefile is now deprecated).

This patch :
 - convert the Modulefile to metadata.json.
 - bump major version to 5 (for juno), and deps.
 - switch to stackforge namespace.
 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

Change-Id: Id33056d659454b3dbc1921e37978993ca46c5217

commit_message:
Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

Since puppet 3.x, Puppet Labs Forge accept only the metadata.json file
for module description (Modulefile is now deprecated).

This patch :
 - convert the Modulefile to metadata.json.
 - bump major version to 5 (for juno), and deps.
 - switch to stackforge namespace.
 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

Change-Id: Iff1f059764547634570b763f04833ddbc01f4758

 - switch to stackforge namespace.
 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

commit_message:
Add ability to configure policy_files_path and policy_files

This change adds the ability to configure policy_files_path
and policy_files configs used by the policy enforcement (RBAC)
support in Horizon.

Closes-bug: #1383458
Change-Id: Iad33e68d09b81b384d4333ef9fa785939d43f9e6

- check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/86/127386/2/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-undercloud-precise-nonha/f1b5201 : FAILURE in 39m 08s
- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/86/127386/2/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-f20-nonha/0b7d0e8 : FAILURE in 1h 06m 13s
- check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha http://logs.openstack.org/86/127386/2/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-ironic-overcloud-precise-nonha/b62b332 : FAILURE in 45m 39s'}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2014-10-10 15:20:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-10-12 20:46:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

I don't like this change, for two reasons.

Firstly, I don't like having os-cloud-config special-cased like this. It seems to be neccessary but it still feels wrong. I think I'd be more comfortable with having a job that builds a package directly from git and then lets setup-clienttools install that package during its normal pip install -U all-the-things process.

Secondly. I don't like the fact that this code is so far removed from the code in setup-clienttools that installs everything else into openstack-tools - anyone trying to troubleshoot issues is likely to end up looking in setup-clienttools and puzzled about why the wrong versions of os-cloud-config got installed. Again, I feel like having pip handle installing the specially-built package during the usual proces would make this clearer - the pip output would show which version was being installed, and from where.

However, to do what I'd like to do requires significantly more time and effort (and perhaps a bit of infrastructure) so I'm happy to see this go in for now to buy us time to get that up and running (if it does turn out to be what we want to do)"}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2014-10-23 18:17:07.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Fixed by making overlay pypi mirror'}]

commit_message:
Switch to Fedora-x86_64-20-20140618-sda

The heat-slow job using the Fedora-20 image as L2 guest, the
currently used version is affected by the heartbleed issue and
the Mb-Bios bug issue observed with emulation.

This version of the  Fedora cloud image uses the no_timer_check
kernel parameter, which solves the MP-Bios Bug issue.

The Image tested with ~3000 heat-slow job, without any issue.

Closes-Bug: #1312199
Closes-Bug: #1297560
(cherry picked from commit bfcb2ff732ffdf2ed50be6a677f1b6182a0213a4)

Conflicts:
	stackrc

Closes-Bug: #1383928

Change-Id: I9ce9b7769c2d91e630b0362f2c2c6ac9066defbc

commit_message:
Keep migration status if instance still resizing

There is a race condition during finish_resize() where
poll_unconfirmed_resizes() can get called between the database save
of the migration record and instance record. The migration record
will be marked 'finished', enabling poll_unconfirmed_resizes() to pick
it up. But the instance will not have been saved yet to have the
vm_state of RESIZED, and task_state of None. The task_state will
still be RESIZE_FINISH. This will cause poll_unconfirmed_resizes() to
put the migration record in error state.

Instead, poll_unconfirmed_resizes() should ignore instances with
a task state of RESIZE_FINISH and not put the migration record
into error state.

Change-Id: I825234de5e4a4f0cc906ac05b715ed85cd953aa1
Closes-Bug: #1376933

Remove auth token from http logging

This redacts the X-Auth-Token header value from the logs by replacing
it with '***'.

commit_message:
Port to use oslo.i18n

Module gettextutils from oslo-incubator was graduated to separate
library (oslo.i18n) and removed from repository, so we should use
new library.

Change-Id: I9bfe95c7995c47715151386c602ef954499bb2ea

commit_message:
Port to use oslo.serialization

Module jsonutils from oslo-incubator was graduated to separate
library (oslo.serialization) and removed from repository, so we
should use new library.

Change-Id: Id2346dd4d69754d97b312c274bf778a0cc0d39fc

commit_message:
Installed builtin reordering everywhere

Installed the builtin reordering code into NonrecursiveRuleTheory
and MaterializedViewTheory.  Added tests for MaterializedViewTheory.
Also tweaked the builtin interface and simplified how other modules
utilize that interface.

Closes-bug: 1350074
Closes-bug: 1350077
Change-Id: I30ec45917686225c43204eafa9364a64ecae3dd7

commit_message:
Added builtin safety and reordering to policy engine

Previously, policy writers needed to ensure that left-to-right evaluation
of the rule body guaranteed that all the inputs for a builtin were bound
before that builtin was evaluated.  Similarly for negation.

This change automates the reordering process, but does so in a way
that leaves the rule unchanged if it is properly ordered.  This ensures
that people can hand-tweak the ordering if they want, but they do
not need to.  It constitutes a first step toward query optimization.

Change-Id: Ia8e522dcec655df6c49a71f748f6280b9df64eeb

commit_message:
Throw HTTP 409 (Conflict) on duplicate rules

Previously, we just returned the ID of the original rule.

We decided it was better to throw a 409.

Change-Id: I641481edf4f55299895b33ef0a0c13cf574d49c0

commit_message:
Added status for datasources and exposed status via API

This change adds get_status() for every datasource and
exposes that information through the API.  Right now,
the status of a datasource consists of (i) the time
the service was last updated and (ii) the last
error that occurred.

Implements: dse-dataservices-status
Change-Id: I75271dc82c7889061f9d125d9205134a0daea817

commit_message:
Add dateutil code

Borrowed (with license) from python-dateutil.  We're copying
code here instead of inserting it as a package.  Because
(1) this package is not supported by OS.
(2) all new OS packages must be python 3 compliant.
(3) this package has a python-3 compliant version and a python-2 version
(4) Congress is not yet python-3 compliant

Change-Id: Idaa29ecd9fc6d12298ca441748f71b6e41262d8f

commit_message:
Xvfb install: Update repo before installing the package

This fixes the following gate failure:
Package xvfb is not available, but is referred to by another package.
This may mean that the package is missing, has been obsoleted, or
is only available from another source

Change-Id: I24b003e4eefce92bb909a87c54dc47009fb064bc

commit_message:
Don't double log API request

If debug logging is enabled the full API call, request and response is
logged, so don't log the request twice.

Change-Id: I45baa04a2daae8fd31c30183ac10464b7affbc21

commit_message:
Flush netcat socket buffer when proxying HTTP connections

HTTP requests from Sahara to Hadoop services can wait indefinitely when
proxied through Neutron namespaces, because buffers are not flushed.
Make sure they are to avoid deadlocks.

Change-Id: Ic1d1b74345be49e405f00264b8c7df3dc06c5b09
Closes-bug: #1384316

When trying to get a cached NeutronHttpAdapter object, use:
  self.adapters.get((host, port), None)
instead of:
  self.adapters.get((host, port), None, *args, **kwargs)
since self.adapters is a dictionary.  Pass *args and **kwargs to the

Closes-Bug: #1383764
'}]
commit_message:
Fix argument list in NeutronClientRemoteWrapper

When trying to get a cached NeutronHttpAdapter object, use:
  self.adapters.get((host, port), None)
instead of:
  self.adapters.get((host, port), None, *args, **kwargs)
since self.adapters is a dictionary.  Pass *args and **kwargs to the
NeutronHttpAdapter constructor.

Change-Id: I0075fa9c59d43b5382606fa166bdb297e25fed2e
Closes-Bug: #1383764

commit_message:
Move the examples docs into the code

I like the idea of having the examples in the code.  I don't necessarily
like having to scroll through all those comments to get to the code.  This
also changes the order of the documentation to summary, example, reference
versus summary, reference, example.  I think I'm okay with that because
:class links will anchor to the reference section.  Normally, seeing a
simple example first can be more useful.

This is a response to Doug's comment:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129937/1/doc/source/user_preference.rst

Change-Id: Ibbda909d2183edc6baeeec0bc56f01779334aabd

commit_message:
Implemented plugin creation and building in fpb

* `fpb --create plugin_name` creates a plugin structure
* `fpb --build plugin_path` builds repository, and
  packs plugin as tar.gz
* add run_tests.sh which runs pep8 checks and unit
  tests for fpb

Change-Id: Id4d108b7427869a5dc0200158d3e2c93c59a33ca
Implements: blueprint cinder-neutron-plugins-in-fuel

commit_message:
Add sorting for releases collection

  Implement sorting for ReleaseCollection in /api/releases
  Sorting criteria:
  1) Fuel version
  2) OpenStack release
  3) Operating system. Ubuntu is preferred

Change-Id: I6677f449b4435aa57c7e4f1c89a292284014d61c
Closes-Bug: 1377920

commit_message:
Add 2 attributes and make nova_url use right scheme

This commit adds nova_ca_certificates_file and
nova_api_insecure so that they can be configured.
It also makes the nova_url use the right scheme.

Closes-Bug: #1383701

This patch needs to be abandoned. As described in StableBranch page on openstack wiki, you need to land a patch in the master branch first, and then propose a backport patch by cherry-picking the patch in the master branch.

One important thing when you propose a backport is to keep Change-Id unchanged. This review can never have the same Change-Id as a patch in the master branch, so this patch is never valid and needs to be abandoned.

Thanks,

This is a professional forum and it's best to keep it that way. Thanks for your good work with Oslo being a core member. That's actually a really good reason you should educate an ignorant one like me :)"}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:18:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Actually I think this is not a technical question here, it depends on how did we define openstack-common.conf. With some talks in IRC, I still think update.py couldn't do all works for us, for example [0], it couldn't maintain imported module files and update config file automatically, and IMO list all the imported modules in openstack-common.conf explicitly could make it more clear. So, I think if we always need to check and update config file by hand why we don't make config file be more clear?

If I miss anything please let me know.

[0] When I do

  $ ./update.sh --nodeps --base glance --dest-dir ../glance --modules policy

even the latest policy.py doesn't use "strutils.py" as a dependency, strutils.py would be removed still, and the related record are still in openstack-common.conf as well: "module=strutils".

Thanks,
zhiyan'}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2014-10-21 14:20:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add ability to deal with migrated volumes

The general migration impl in Cinder works
by creating a new volume, transfering the data
from the original volume to the new volume, and
then deleting the original and flipping the ID
of the new volume.

This requires some work on the backend device to
update it's ID/Name so it knows how to find the
requested volume after a migration.

Currently the SF driver would just look for the
volume, however the only volume it would have available
is the newly created volume which has a different UUID.

This patch utilizes the newly added update_migrated_volume
call to verify things after a migration.

The real fix however is that on a volume-create we check to
see if this creation is part of a migration operation, if it
is we need to set Fake out the Volume-Name ahead of time
because we can't change it after the fact without jumping through
a boat load of hoops.  This works well in our case because we
allow duplicate names.

Change-Id: Icf4b2d17dea5642afa308b2b99ad0cc4fc317c80
Closes-Bug: #1381943

commit_message:
Port to use oslo.utils

Module importutils, timeutils from oslo-incubator was graduated to
separate library (oslo.utils) and removed from repository, so we
should use new library.

Change-Id: I74c23960dd2783385cc5eae9b6e2df3202b0a2bf

As suggested I took a look at pypi-mirrors, looks like it 
would do what I want but would require more code and 
dependencies, from what I can see I would be replacing the two 
echo >> index.html commands with something like


    virtualenv venv
    . venv/bin/activate
    cd /opt/stack/new/pypi-mirror
    pip install -r requirements.txt
    pip install .
    mkdir -p ~jenkins/.cache/image-create/pypi/cache/pip/mirror ~jenkins/.cache/image-create/pypi/cache/wheelhouse

    cat >>/tmp/pypi-mirror.yaml<<-EOF
    cache-root: /home/derekh/.cache/image-create/pypi/cache
    mirrors:
      - name: mirror
        output: /home/derekh/.cache/image-create/pypi/mirror
    EOF

    python ./pypi_mirror/cmd/run_mirror.py -c /tmp/pypi-mirror.yaml --no-download'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Work In Progress

(2 comments)

As an alternative approach, I'm wondering if devpi (http://doc.devpi.net) might serve our needs.

I think this would mean reaplcing the two echo >> index.html commands with something like:

virtualenv venv
. venv/bin/activate
pip install devpi
devpi quickstart
devpi user -c testenvuser password=
devpi login testenvuser --password=

Outside the virtualenv, `devpi use --set-cfg` will configure pip/distutils/buildout to use the devpi mirror

then, for each package we want to install from git:

cd $PACKAGE_CHECKOUT
rm -rf dist
python setup.py sdist
devpi upload dist/*

after this, simply using "pip install" will load our custom packages from devpi; anything we haven't uploaded will be fetched from upstream.

This does introduce some complexity, in the form of the extra devpi process/web server that's now running and needs to stay running so that packages can be installed. However, maybe that's preferable to us trying to replicate this functionality in a few lines of shell....'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2014-10-14 16:52:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-14 16:52:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Build a local pip mirror of python packages being tested

Build a pypi mirror in ~/.cache/image-create/pypi/mirror/ , exposing
this over http allows us to use this as the main pip index where ci
built trunk packages can be installed from (for the projects being
tested by ZUUL).

Co-Authored-By: Gregory Haynes <greg@greghaynes.net>
Change-Id: I33d2b6fbfadb259861a6d961ceac5c0e97de2904

commit_message:
Neutron HA composition model

* Refactor part of the corosync/pacemaker resources to be outside of the neutron module
* Adaption cluster::corosync::cs_service to asymetric cluster

This allows for seperate management of the HA scripts and classes from the
neutron module and will allow the module to continue to track upstream with
out modifiation in regards to HA support

Authors: Andrew Woodward, Sergey Vasilenko

partial blueprint: merge-openstack-puppet-modules
blueprint: ml2-neutron

Fuel-CI: disable
Change-Id: If471a371c11a26f5b4182bc3afcf391d00012666

commit_message:
Raise the new OperationTimedOut when futures don't finish

When a future hasn't finished in time it will raise a
specific exception that we should reraise as the new wrapped
error so that users of tooz can nicely handle time outs in
a uniform manner.

Change-Id: Id0b0965e5dcd66e0338fd57294236a14aff4b3d1

commit_message:
Add a temp workaround for an issue #153 in rabbit cookbook

After configuring rabbitmq, restart the service to make configuration
take effect. So during OpenStack deployment, OpenStack services can
connect to rabbitmq successfully.
This workaround will notify rabbitmq-server to restart immediately.
This could be remove once the issue #153 is fixed in rabbit cookbook.

Change-Id: Ib017226f46c7e26429bb26df5b63525e1a98bc82
Closes-Bug: #1380940

commit_message:
Purge old neutron manifests and move our customized files

outside from community neutron manifest.

This makes it easier to carry rebases forward and prevent conflicts.
This may be squased into the merge from upstream commit.

Authors: Andrew Woodward, Sergey Vasilenko

blueprint: ml2-neutron

Fuel-CI: disable
Change-Id: I9b69c2ab4cb4e476083ec9516f442d9b1911b666

commit_message:
Start to add a catch and reraise of timed out exceptions

When the kazoo operation times out it will raise a kazoo handler
specific exception which we should ensure we catch and reraise
as a tooz specific one to make it easier for users of tooz to
catch and handle driver timeouts.

Change-Id: I9caa1e8e550e3cba04fc139ede897e2a7c511f79

commit_message:
Construct and pass action_context to action

If action_context is defined in the init method of an action, a
dictionary of execution and task information is constructed and passed
as input parameters to the init method.

Change-Id: I25627a0bc94c5b55a33b71602f44d7297e2a0c10
Closes-Bug: 1380873

commit_message:
Switch to metadata.json for Puppet forge releases

Since puppet 3.x, Puppet Labs Forge accept only the metadata.json file
for module description (Modulefile is now deprecated).

This patch :
 - convert the Modulefile to metadata.json.
 - bump major version to 5 (for juno), and deps.
 - switch to stackforge namespace.
 - relax pe version_requirement to 3.x.

Change-Id: I7056bb05a33ce24f1f0b0b363de0f848e49eb299

subject: Horizon integration tests require Xvfb
messages:
[{'account_id': 4978, 'date': '2014-10-14 15:06:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 4978, 'date': '2014-10-14 15:07:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

An example of the current failures can be seen at [1]. Based on the job's dpkg output at [2] and local tests I'm fairly sure this is happening because Xvfb is unavailable on the node.

 [1] http://logs.openstack.org/74/102274/5/experimental/gate-horizon-dsvm-integration/281d25a/console.html
 [2] http://logs.openstack.org/74/102274/5/experimental/gate-horizon-dsvm-integration/281d25a/logs/dpkg-l.txt.gz"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-14 15:22:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

- gate-infra-puppet-apply-centos6 http://logs.openstack.org/25/128325/1/check/gate-infra-puppet-apply-centos6/ac2faf8 : SUCCESS in 5m 36s'}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2014-10-15 20:48:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

So I have no quibble if horizon wants to install something that suits them. This doesn't appear to be any kind of a security risk. The code for creating the macro looks correct to me.

What I am curious about is why this is necessary. In requirements xvfbwrapper is listed: http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/requirements/tree/global-requirements.txt#n230 so does installing xvfbwrapper assume that xvfb is present? It feels like xvfb used to be present without being specifically installed and went away for some reason. Do we know why?"}, {'account_id': 4978, 'date': '2014-10-16 09:22:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Xvfbwrapper requires Xvfb to work indeed. This integration job is new though, and has never worked yet so it's not something that's become broken. Jobs running unit tests that depend on Xvfb still run fine.

My current guess is that it's because devstack nodes (as is required for the integration tests here) are "thin" while the bare nodes that run the unit tests are "thick" and that means they install the xvfb package too: https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack-infra/config/tree/modules/openstack_project/manifests/thick_slave.pp?id=7fff4e7e933643bae05a9d559bf4f7dad594685e#n52'}, {'account_id': 6316, 'date': '2014-10-20 16:21:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Devstack uses thin nodes, unit tests and docs use thick nodes. Integration tests using devstack must use thin nodes hence installing this lib is necessary.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-23 14:09:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.

commit_message:
Horizon integration tests require Xvfb

Xvfb isn't installed by default on devstack nodes. Since it's a
requirement for the Horizon integration tests, create a new macro to
install it only for the jobs where it is needed.

Change-Id: I168fe5f1e6253ded89728ee2a69f8cf3197d2000

commit_message:
Make sure that AutoScalingGroup depends on the launch config

It seems to be common error to do the following:
  LaunchConfigurationName: my_config
and not include a depends_on.

Largely because of the unfortunate property name.
So this patch tries to make sure the user has the
correct dependency in place.

Change-Id: I4f7d282d0af8681dc2c8cd265e16a27fe23a3bdb
Closes-bug: #1375777

commit_message:
Fix locator typo in go_to_accesssecurity_page

Method is_element_visible expects locator that should consist of two
items -> missing '*'.

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I1ec86cf37fe0e1dc4b3d68d884f60a2c04adb380

commit_message:
apt-ftparchive*.conf: don't hard code Ubuntu version

Use the UBUNTU_RELEASE and (the newly introduced) UBUNTU_RELEASE_NUMBER
variables instead.

The idea is to have a single place (config.mk) where the Ubuntu (kernel,
whatever) versions are defined (instead of spreading that data over 10+ files)

commit_message:
requirements-deb.txt: omit redundant packages

 * don't list packages pulled by ubuntu-minimal/ubuntu-standard metapackages
 * don't list the dependencies of build-essential metapackage
 * don't list nova, neutron, cinder, and glance dependencies

Skip the prerequisites of the following packages:

 * apache2
 * aptitude
 * cloud-init
 * corosync
 * cpu-checker
 * crda
 * discover
 * gdisk
 * git
 * grub-pc
 * guestmount
 * libgtk2.0 (not sure why we need libgtk itself)
 * libparse-debianchangelog-perl
 * libvte9 (why do we need this one?)
 * lksctp-tools
 * mysql
 * nodejs
 * novnc
 * pacemaker
 * python-utidylib
 * python-zmq
 * qemu-kvm
 * ruby-ohai
 * rabbitmq-server
 * tasksel
 * xauth
 * xinetd

Also added a script which helps to reduce dependencies.

Note: the obtained requirements-deb.txt still contains redundant and
extraneous entries, this issue will be handled later on.

Change-Id: Ic0d143a6f6e2eae01b721bae4fd3b6b748558c3b
Related-bug: #1383641

commit_message:
Prepend '/dev/' to supplied dev names in the API

Make sure that all user input device names end up in the database with
the '/dev/' prefix. This will make things more consistent and avoid
issues when attempting to parse device names.

This includes two main sources - block device mapping that can be passed
as part of a request or as image metadata, and root device name, passed
as image metadata.

Closes-bug: #1337821
Change-Id: Ibda82f511be99f1a68f2f77c72601a1b006be7a0

commit_message:
Remove E12* from list of deliberately ignored flake8 rules

I367064ecaa6d1fd9d918f7ce003303e2db660647  Added E12 to the
ignored on purpose list, which also makes no sense E12 was never meant
to be skipped all together (I was the one who added E12 to the flake8
ignore list (Ifc8924914b5a0d625bc8df6442ee85eb21459cde)

Then I4cf246e3ec932ba0d2391eb8bcb793b28b005b4c came along and updated
the list to break out the E12 ignored on purpose list.

Drop all E12 rules from the ignored on purpose list, as we do not want
to ignore these on purpose.

Change-Id: Ic400047347a82aebbc0f6ce6f5061e7757a02d3d

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-21 10:39:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-ceilometer-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/25/129825/1/check/gate-ceilometer-specs-docs/d716e93/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 05s
- gate-ceilometer-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/25/129825/1/check/gate-ceilometer-specs-python27/1cc0a69 : SUCCESS in 4m 12s'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-10-22 11:46:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Few things:

* It looks like you may have amended the commit at HEAD rather than starting a new one for this submission. For the first commit you want to do commit -a (without --amend). Only later do you want to --amend the commit. The clue is that the wrong author is on this commit, and the change to fake.rst is included. Probably the easiest thing to do is copy your file somewhere safe, abandon this change, create a new branch, and then commit that.
* In the text of your file please do not use \r line-endings nor tabs.

On the spec itself, I'm not sure there's really enough detail to understand how this is supposed to work or why. If I understand correctly the idea is for a pollster to regularly ping each instance and if it does not get a response change heartbeat from 1 to 0.

I don't think this will be efficient, reliable or unambiguous. There are _many_ reasons why a ping to an instance will not succeed and only one of them is because the instance is dead.

Is there not some way the the virt inspector can inquire after an instance's health?"}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-10-23 08:29:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 10472, 'date': '2014-10-23 13:02:14.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

A new spec will be opened instead of this one.'}]

commit_message:
Support an auto restart on an instance shutdown

Adding a heartbeat pollster to Ceilometer
which checks the instance health using a ping command

blueprint instance-autorestart

Change-Id: I61449490699b888135a1a9c764f9f8b14fafd665

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-18 17:09:25.000000000', 'message': 'Add instance ID validation stage

Reasons:
 - user is able to create incremental backup
   using parent backup taken from another instance.

Changes:
 - adding instance validation stage while
   attempting to create incremental backup;
 - unit/int tests proposed.

Behaviour:
 - when when attempting to create incremental backup by using
   parent from different instance server side
   will raise ParentBackupIDMismatch exception;
 - from user perspective exception will be interpreted
   as HTTP Conflict(409).

Change-Id: Ia9a1efca03bd52461273298bac332ec897102aea
Closes-Bug: #1344133

 - adding instance validation stage while
   attempting to create incremental backup;

Behaviour:
 - when when attempting to create incremental backup by using
   parent from different instance server side
   will raise ParentBackupIDMismatch exception;
 - from user perspective exception will be interpreted
   as HTTP Forbidden(403) according to RFC 2616 -- Trove server site
   understood the request, but is refusing to fulfill
   it due to IDs mismatch.

commit_message:
Add instance ID validation stage while creating incremental backup

Reasons:
 - user is able to create incremental backup
   using parent backup taken from another instance.

Changes:
 - adding instance validation stage while
   attempting to create incremental backup;
 - unit/int tests proposed.

Behaviour:
 - when attempting to create incremental backup by using
   parent from different instance server side
   will raise ParentBackupIDMismatch exception;
 - from user perspective exception will be interpreted
   as HTTP Forbidden(403) according to RFC 2616 -- Trove server site
   understood the request, but is refusing to fulfill
   it due to IDs mismatch.

Change-Id: Ia9a1efca03bd52461273298bac332ec897102aea
Closes-Bug: #1344133

commit_message:
mkrepo.sh: bail out if packages are not installable

... instead of producing a broken local mirror. Also provide a hint
what exactly went wrong (which package had unmet dependencies, etc).

Closes-bug: #1368137

Change-Id: Ifa7e86d706bea025b2deb3f9ace1be2909110e72

commit_message:
Fix incremental backups feature validation

Reasons:
 - Not all strategies have incremental backup strategy.
   Existing example: MySQLDump.
   Future: CbBackup, MongoDump, NodetoolSnapshot.

Changes:
 - incremental backups feature validation stage added;
 - adding fix to fake guest;
 - unit/fake-int tests proposed.

Behaviour:
 - server side will raise IncrementalBackupNotSupported;
 - from client perspective this error will interpreted
   as HTTP NotImplemented(501).

Change-Id: I025cf24f776bbff934a7522b9fa1e68e48f42c38
Closes-Bug: #1340175

commit_message:
Virt driver pinning guest vCPUs to host pCPUs

This feature aims to improve the libvirt driver so that it is
able to strictly pin guest vCPUS to host pCPUs. This provides
the concept of "dedicated CPU" guest instances.

Change-Id: I29e2f3cbf45ae36c6c6b7a089d46cc6710bfbbe0

changes to features.rst

changed to designed to enable a user - a before user

commit_message:
Update multiple backend configuration in tempest script

Currently when we configure the tempest with multiple LVM
backends the backend names are created as LVM_iSCSI and
LVM_iSCSI_2 which fails since the backends created by cinder
are lvmdriver-1 and lvmdriver-2.

This patch updates the backend names. Added support for
CINDER_ENABLED_BACKENDS and added todo to remove
CINDER_MULTI_LVM_BACKEND once its formally removed

Closes-Bug:#1369946
Closes-Bug:#1369942

Change-Id: If44f5eb206616afb0fbaf333f3fa6a296d4650cd

commit_message:
Add dpkg tools to manage Ubuntu repo from CentOS

dpkg-scanpackages has similar functionality as
apt-ftparchive but has port to CentOS6.x

Related-Bug: 1358785
Implements: blueprint testing-packages-in-enviroment

Change-Id: I39e126dd02c84787602944a01d9f309754a510ca

commit_message:
Adds tty password entry for ironicclient

Added functionality from keystoneclient to fallback to the tty for password
entry if no password is given via the environment or the --os-password option.

Change-Id: I92da7112221c77efc220374617d503dc2184363e
Closes-Bug: 1382146

commit_message:
Add missing parameters for server rescue

The server rescue call supports passing a password and an image,
however novaclient does not have options to support this. This commit
adds these options and updates the related unit tests to support the
change.

Change-Id: I14c878c0027f8206671ee001ba5195f94f842314

commit_message:
Console: delete code for VMRCConsole and VMRCSessionConsole

In Juno there was warning that this code will be removed in Kilo.
This patch deletes the VMRC console classes for the ESX and VC drivers.
This code has not worked since the Icehouse release.

Change-Id: If2d1e237f92eb080dadc2eee1f2f2771a06ce2f6

commit_message:
VMware: delete the driver VMwareESXDriver

In Juno we had a deprcation warning about the VMwareESXDriver no
longer being supported. This class is now deleted.

Change-Id: Id5b50fa944f57cd8fd61611d93caac8066cfd93d

commit_message:
no way to delete valid/invalid security rule

Previously deleting valid/invalid security
group rules was throwing the error of
"AttributeError". With this fix, now both
types of security group rules can be deleted.

Change-Id: I253c2742efe69ee41976c88ca2775189bc5bde0d
Closes-Bug: #1163469

commit_message:
Use instance object in resource_tracker

The resource tracker is being converted to use objects. This patch
removes the conductor call to instance_update and replaces it with a
call to Instance#save.

Furthers bp make-resource-tracker-use-objects

Change-Id: I73fbfc951f9ac51e991f3884e85c67512359f9e3

commit_message:
VMware: rename vmware_images to images

There is no need for the prefix vmware. vmware_images.py has been
renamed to images.py and test_vmware_images.py has been renamed
to test_images.py.

Change-Id: Icbc64da072f60713c1a79aca2ed503dcd7586063

commit_message:
remove reference to model in migration

the model represents the current active representation.
migrations on the other hand represent some moment in past that
may or may not reflect the current model. we shouldn't reference
model unless we have to.

Change-Id: I78dca9043014acc1a6eda479f687f63d31ce1ea7

commit_message:
Cisco VPNaaS and router integration

Spec for completion of the effort to integrate the Cisco VPNaaS
plugin with the L3 router plugin to use an in-band Cisco CSR
router.

Change-Id: I7d590c29c1815377f3b95f4574e38823bb1b6f18
Implements: blueprint cisco-vpnaas-and-router-integration

Add create_database_permission_exist function

If user doesn't have permission to create database we
get incomprehensible error message when run tests.
Additional check to test whether user has permission
was added to get clear message error.

all tables use utf-8 encoding.

- gate-oslo.db-python33 http://logs.openstack.org/46/124446/1/check/gate-oslo.db-python33/7c9eb0b : FAILURE in 38s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-27 18:57:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

This is kind of a nitpicky change, and if we're going for nitpicky changes with the goal towards "can improve performance", the bar is IMHO high for those.  We can't just say, "iterators are faster than lists", implement code that happens to use more iterator tools, and then just claim performance has improved.   Python is nothing like that, because as an interpreted language, function call overhead is a super killer that usually dwarfs any gains spent for lists/iterators, especially if we are talking about very small amounts of data.   

In this case the proposed function uses five function calls at the top and three within the loop, compared to the original which uses five at the top but only one within half the loop (the startswith()).    It looks a lot slower to me so in the efforts to improve the story when small changes like this are proposed, I've created a test suite at http://paste.openstack.org/show/116011/ which illustrates what has to be done if we are to claim performance gains with small functions.   I've included a fixed up version of the original, the proposed function, and an alternative which is how I'd probably do it.    The proposed function is 38% - 600% slower than the original function in all cases, depending on number of items and what proportion of those items are in `__dict__` vs. `iter(self)`:


$ python test.py
--------------------------------------
original code, dictsize 10 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 0.139145
proposed code, dictsize 10 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 0.180312
alternative code, dictsize 10 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 0.108251
--------------------------------------
original code, dictsize 1000 itersize 1000 iterations 10000: 5.680760
proposed code, dictsize 1000 itersize 1000 iterations 10000: 11.751014
alternative code, dictsize 1000 itersize 1000 iterations 10000: 6.280172
--------------------------------------
original code, dictsize 10000 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 48.198194
proposed code, dictsize 10000 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 59.473258
alternative code, dictsize 10000 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 37.997403
--------------------------------------
original code, dictsize 10 itersize 10000 iterations 1000: 0.921628
proposed code, dictsize 10 itersize 10000 iterations 1000: 5.855081
alternative code, dictsize 10 itersize 10000 iterations 1000: 2.431076

In reality, these are model objects which will have a dozen or so columns in `__dict__` and probably half that or less in relationships, so the top case is the one that is closest what is typical. 

That said, the original function is fine, my alternative takes a pure iterator approach and is a bit faster, but overall it's not critical in any case.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-27 18:59:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

here's that table formatted:

	$ python test.py
	--------------------------------------
	original code, dictsize 10 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 0.139145
	proposed code, dictsize 10 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 0.180312
	alternative code, dictsize 10 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 0.108251
	--------------------------------------
	original code, dictsize 1000 itersize 1000 iterations 10000: 5.680760
	proposed code, dictsize 1000 itersize 1000 iterations 10000: 11.751014
	alternative code, dictsize 1000 itersize 1000 iterations 10000: 6.280172
	--------------------------------------
	original code, dictsize 10000 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 48.198194
	proposed code, dictsize 10000 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 59.473258
	alternative code, dictsize 10000 itersize 10 iterations 10000: 37.997403
	--------------------------------------
	original code, dictsize 10 itersize 10000 iterations 1000: 0.921628
	proposed code, dictsize 10 itersize 10000 iterations 1000: 5.855081
	alternative code, dictsize 10 itersize 10000 iterations 1000: 2.431076"}, {'account_id': 12363, 'date': '2014-10-23 10:25:13.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Implement db.ModelBase.iteritems() as a generator

It is better to use generators if it is possible, because
we don't create extra arrays and we can improve perfomance

Closes-Bug: #1119727

Co-Authored-By: Boris Pavlovic <boris@pavlovic.me>

Change-Id: Ibbe734540aa6fd32c9f7dd4667e4d00b9465af6f

commit_message:
Add functional API tests for cron-triggers

- Added API tests which check main api calls to cron-trigger endpoint
- Fixed tearDown method (there was a problem when item array
had a few elements, not all of them were deleted)

Partly implements: blueprint mistral-triggers-functional-tests

Change-Id: Ibba7cd03e6ccdf06c76ea4ea161542b954faee0f

commit_message:
Adapt upstream puppet-neutron into fuel

Fix up new entry points
Refactor openstack:: to enter neutron instead of old sanitize_network
Plug in new neutron HA composition
Add in some changes that need to make it back into upstream eventually.

blueprint: ml2-neutron
partial-blueprint: merge-openstack-puppet-modules

commit_message:
Neutron HA composition model

Refactor all of the corosync resources to be outside of the neutron module

This allows for seperate management of the HA scripts and classes from the
neutron module and will allow the module to continue to track upstream with
out modifiation in regards to HA support

partial blueprint: merge-openstack-puppet-modules
blueprint: ml2-neutron

Fuel-CI: disable
Change-Id: If471a371c11a26f5b4182bc3afcf391d000124aa

Adaptation cluster::corosync::cs_service to asymetric cluster

1. Current asymmetric cluster requires another menipulations with services
2. fix searching Service<||> resources by title

partial blueprint: merge-openstack-puppet-modules
blueprint: ml2-neutron

Fuel-CI: disable
Change-Id: I242703748acfd993539593f4fe4dfeeb4707eaf1

commit_message:
Fix chains around Service["${service_name}-disable-init"]

It's affects Ubuntu on some cases.

Closes-bug: #1382535
Fuel-CI:  disable
Change-Id: Ib9373d1079d5f6390a70adfc5d2b4e348668d631

[{'created': '2014-10-23 01:01:55.000000000', 'message': 'Delete unused 'use_ipv6' config option

The 'use_ipv6' config option is not being used, and Ironic doesn't support
IPv6 (see https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1325942). Someone may
try to set this value to True, and that wouldn't do anything, so it is
better to delete it and add it back in the future when IPv6 is supported.

I'm not sure it needs a DocImpact since it never worked, but I'll tag
it, just in case we want to document that "the 'use_ipv6' config option
was deleted because it never worked".

Closes-Bug: #1384509
DocImpact

Change-Id: I7704067ca50448ffb0982e653437d151af85471f
'}]
commit_message:
Delete unused 'use_ipv6' config option

The 'use_ipv6' config option is not being used, and Ironic doesn't support
IPv6 (see https://bugs.launchpad.net/ironic/+bug/1325942). Someone may
try to set this value to True, and that wouldn't do anything, so it is
better to delete it and add it back in the future when IPv6 is supported.

I'm not sure it needs a DocImpact since it never worked, but I'll tag
it, just in case we want to document that "the 'use_ipv6' config option
was deleted because it never worked".

Closes-Bug: #1384509
DocImpact

Change-Id: I7704067ca50448ffb0982e653437d151af85471f

[{'created': '2014-09-30 13:32:16.000000000', 'message': "Improve error messages generated by test_unshelve

This change rewrites test_unshelve and test_unshelve_volume_backed to
use mock in place of mox. The primary purpose of this is to improve
the error message generated in the event of a failure. Bug 1375688
appears to be a non-deterministic test failure in test_unshelve, but
the generated error messages are not immediately enlightening.

This change moves the 2 unshelve tests in to their own test class, as
this allows them to have common setup code. We also refactor the call
to unshelve_instance into _unshelve_instance, which contains all
assertions common to both tests. We convert mox assertions to mock
assertions mechanically.

As we make a number of assertions about call values, and the purpose
of this change is to trap a non-deterministic failure, we use
expectThat() in place of regular mock assertions. The advantage of
this is that should any mock assertion fail, they will all be logged
before ultimately failing, which will be useful for later debugging.
Note that we don't appear to be using testtools.RunTest, which is
required for the correct function of expectThat. This requires a
slightly unpleasant manual dance to ensure we catch expection
failures.

Change-Id: I9175c8a61ce959e31aad3dacf38a436d237a093f
Related-Bug: #1375688
"}, {'created': '2014-10-02 12:38:31.000000000', 'message': 'Make test_unshelve deterministic

This change rewrites test_unshelve to no longer use a subclass of
test_compute.BaseTestCase. This means that the test no longer uses a
real database, which is a source of non-deterministic unit test
failure in the gate.

This is a complete rewrite from scratch, and should be examined
accordingly.

Closes-Bug: #1375688
Change-Id: I9175c8a61ce959e31aad3dacf38a436d237a093f
'}]
commit_message:
Make test_unshelve deterministic

This change rewrites test_unshelve to no longer use a subclass of
test_compute.BaseTestCase. This means that the test no longer uses a
real database, which is a source of non-deterministic unit test
failure in the gate.

This is a complete rewrite from scratch, and should be examined
accordingly.

Closes-Bug: #1375688
Change-Id: I9175c8a61ce959e31aad3dacf38a436d237a093f

commit_message:
Fix sed regex for deleting old configs

Ic968f39b16934c9e55d9aa448cbd9de54f659d4d removed the "auto $bridge" line
from the bridge configuration so we need to update the sed to continue to
remove that section, which now starts with the "allow-ovs $bridge" line instead

Change-Id: I76df0d00f2f01e2945570b94abfb78dd73c7b240

@Srinivas, I'm afraid that the max_retries is used in oslo.db, please see the "for" iteration at https://github.com/openstack/oslo.db/blob/master/oslo/db/sqlalchemy/session.py#L547. The reason that you didn't hit the max*max retry situation might be that the invalid situation you simulated on your test environment caused exceptions other than DBConnectionError. If other error conditions caused DBConnectionError, than max_retries comes into the play.

[{'created': '2014-10-09 03:47:57.000000000', 'message': 'Allow collector service database connection re-try when db server goes offline

At the startup collector service loads the database dispatcher, if the DB is offline
momentarily the collector service starts but continues to run with out having the ability
to re-try the DB connection. This fix will allow the connection to be retried next time
when collector service attempts to write to the database.

commit_message:
Allow collector service database connection retry

At the startup collector service loads the database dispatcher,
if the DB is offline momentarily the collector service starts but
continues to run with out having the ability to re-try the DB
connection. This fix will allow the connection to be retried next
time when collector service attempts to write to the database.

Change-Id: I10fef61a9c525e1c84d8cadbca86d6bde84927ba
Closes-Bug: 1301777

commit_message:
Point all puppet projects at puppet-system.config

The differences between these files are marginal and for most
projects they were just copying each other directly

The only anomaly of note is puppet-yum with:

requireContributorAgreement = true

But it's unclear to me whether we actually want this, so I lumped
this in with the rest of the acl merge.

Change-Id: Iae0b0e93ab66b7ecc3a9f8fa3c355b241bd39e27

commit_message:
add circular check when updating region

Now, we can make a circle in hierarchical regions via updating region,
this can lead to endless loop when deleting region.
Add a check when updating region to ensure no circle in hierarchical
regions.

Change-Id: Id0ce214c9560c4c2c5251769136f1319082c1d8f
loses-Bug: #1383676

commit_message:
Purge old neutron manifests and move our customized files

outside from community neutron manifest.

This makes it easier to carry rebases forward and prevent conflicts.
This may be squased into the merge from upstream commit.

blueprint: ml2-neutron

Fuel-CI: disable
Change-Id: I9b69c2ab4cb4e476083ec9516f442d9b1911b2a7

commit_message:
Check for IPv6 file before reading

Check to see if the IPv6 disabled flag file exists
before trying to read it. This file doesn't exist
on systems with the IPv6 module blacklisted.

Closes-Bug: #1361542
Change-Id: I4064b4189cc9d8f0f0e0e7025cf6f83d5b6ec276

commit_message:
Add init methods to javascript

Currently, we have old javascripts that automatically  get initialized when
the document is ready. This patch provides a mechanism to access those
initialization code by assigning them a name.

Change-Id: I59aa4abf6c68675f7c5f2802682d73fb7beb7613
Closes-bug: #1347072

commit_message:
iso element to build bootable ISO images

This commit adds a new element named 'iso' to build a bootable
ISO image for the kernel/ramdisk emitted by the 'baremetal' or
'ramdisk' element.

Change-Id: I89d175a29e2d0bc64b47fe527f0d0f6875f6849a

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-22 23:23:06.000000000', 'message': 'Fix an issue with setting tempest volume vendor_name with spaces

If the volume vendor has spaces in it, for example “Open Source”, we
need to have quotes around the uses of the variables or the behavior
will not be as expected.

Change-Id: Ie1e99b6d6de2313e5b5b5a5d3057c136c9b34601
'}]
commit_message:
Fix an issue with setting tempest volume vendor_name with spaces

If the volume vendor has spaces in it, for example “Open Source”, we
need to have quotes around the uses of the variables or the behavior
will not be as expected.

Change-Id: Ie1e99b6d6de2313e5b5b5a5d3057c136c9b34601

commit_message:
set xml_api flag for Network tests

XML api support is being removed in Kilo, so we need to enable here to
ensure that the API is still tested in this stable release.

Change-Id: Iaf0cb93fda607c62911c57132eced14a33f94f97

[{'created': '2014-05-27 22:14:20.000000000', 'message': 'An IO optimised method for accessing resource data

This provides a wrapper over the db_api.resource_data_* methods that
attempts to avoid unnecessary database calls for get operations.

On resource create, all resource data is loaded with a single query and
stored with the resource as a dict. Calling data_set() or data_delete()
clears this dict so the next time data() is called all resource
data is loaded again from the database.

There is a future potential optimisation to prefetch the resource.data on
resource_get_by_name_and_stack, which would result in zero resource data
queries for a Stack.load.

This is part of an effort to reduce the number of database queries required
for a Stack.load operation.

Change-Id: I2564a9f953841d895acd5b853a67aa4bc375b635
Related-Bug: #1306743
'}]
commit_message:
An IO optimised method for accessing resource data

This provides a wrapper over the db_api.resource_data_* methods that
attempts to avoid unnecessary database calls for get operations.

On resource create, all resource data is loaded with a single query and
stored with the resource as a dict. Calling data_set() or data_delete()
clears this dict so the next time data() is called all resource
data is loaded again from the database.

There is a future potential optimisation to prefetch the resource.data on
resource_get_by_name_and_stack, which would result in zero resource data
queries for a Stack.load.

This is part of an effort to reduce the number of database queries required
for a Stack.load operation.

Change-Id: I2564a9f953841d895acd5b853a67aa4bc375b635
Related-Bug: #1306743

commit_message:
libvirt: use six.text_type when setting text node value in guest xml

Trying to spawn an instance with a unicode name using the libvirt driver
fails with a UnicodeDecodeError because the value is cast to str().

The fix is to use six.text_type for the cast.

Closes-Bug: #1382318

Change-Id: I4628b94459a3c1e757d388916f1268884cb02038

commit_message:
Add config option to override url for versions

The versions url returns the wrong data when glance api is behind
a proxy. This adds a new config option so it can be set properly.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I5ab53d608a6667435a4b03b0c832870716baaeb8
Closes-Bug: #1384379

[{'created': '2014-10-23 00:39:30.000000000', 'message': 'Use Python 2.7 when installing zuul on workers

* nodepool/scripts/prepare_node.sh: The py3k-precise nodes use a
virtualenv which defaults to python3.3, and zuul has at least one
dependency which fails to install in this situation (python-daemon
tries to use a non-Py3K compliant print syntax in its
version_info.py module). By telling virtualenv to use python2.7
instead we sidestep this issue.

Change-Id: Idfa70dee91494da83380fa0c0a1f8427659f6ce2
'}, {'created': '2014-10-23 00:43:07.000000000', 'message': 'Use Python 2 when installing zuul on workers

virtualenv which defaults to python3.3, and zuul has at least one
dependency which fails to install in this situation (python-daemon

commit_message:
Use Python 2 when installing zuul on workers

* nodepool/scripts/prepare_node.sh: The py3k-precise nodes use a
virtualenv which defaults to python3.3, and zuul has at least one
dependency which fails to install in this situation (python-daemon
tries to use a non-Py3K compliant print syntax in its
version_info.py module). By telling virtualenv to use python2
instead we sidestep this issue.

Change-Id: Idfa70dee91494da83380fa0c0a1f8427659f6ce2

commit_message:
VMware: remove mountpoint from VMwareVolumeOps

The VMware driver is not able to mount volumes at specified mountpoint,
so this argument is not used at all in VMwareVolumeOps. This patch
removes the 'mountpoint' argument from all attach/detach methods.

Change-Id: Ie65bb5f9202cb27b77772312ba542f6a8a3d9688

commit_message:
Fix exit of subprocess in case it was terminated by signal

If child process of rootwrap is terminated by signal, exit code should
be 128 + N, where N is number of signal. According [1]
subprocess.Popen.returncode returns -N. sys.exit interprets negative
signed byte as unsigned thus original exit code is 256 - N instead of
128 + N.

[1]
https://docs.python.org/2/library/subprocess.html#subprocess.Popen.returncode

Change-Id: I43b4c959a98f8f620466c77de4cd5b724b09e5a8
Closes-Bug: #1364822

commit_message:
Make sure iniset replaces commented out options

If the option passed to iniset already exists but is commented out, it will be
uncommented and its value will be changed.

Change-Id: I99c0d356758d767f5a4cd02107deaa4d51de1e74
Closes-Bug: #1383843

commit_message:
Allow register-node to accept int for input

register-node used to pipe the nodes definition file through jq, which
explicitly converts all int values to strings, but the new
implementation doesn't do so, which is backward incompatible.

Change-Id: Id5c5b56ccd73bdabe02eb24575e5b8c4dbcdb04b
Closes-Bug: #1382275

Include support for using oslo debugger in tests

Simply run `tox -e debug <test_name>` to get an interactive
debugging prompt

commit_message:
add Column attribute for help tooltip in heading

To use: add attribute help_text=_("foo") to tables.Column(...)
This will add a help icon next to the Column name which
you can hover-over to get informational text.

Change-Id: I10a28bd51efbaf83c617b30b31d861445418f9d8
Closes-Bug: #1381633

commit_message:
Nova api service doesn't handle SIGHUP properly

When SIGHUP signal is sent to nova-api service, it doesn't complete
processing of all pending requests before terminating all the
processes.

Closes-Bug: #1334647

Change-Id: I3f7bd0ba5ef1bb716a97635252abe251053a669d
(cherry picked from commit 224a3de466d48301ab638b60ca47d19ad6b1b1dc)

commit_message:
[Sahara] Support Nova availability zones

Add an optional field in the node group template page.  It is used for
selecting the availability zone where to spawn instances.

Change-Id: Id504ec3d0d8a398f79cc45568169e67f54a6a9b8
Implements: blueprint support-nova-availability-zones

commit_message:
Make duration in serial test approximate total run time

The duration argument is supposed to mean how long the test will take to
finish. Before this change, if running serially it would take n*duration where
n is the number of test cases specified to run.

Change-Id: I9bd525b17e41fae811e3bf48642b728151e65737

commit_message:
Add list servers to large ops test

Add regression test for bug 1282842, which is hit when running nova list while
waiting for instances to move to ACTIVE.

commit_message:
Make screen_service() useful for more than services

screen_service() can currently only be used to launch things that
pass the 'is_service_enabled' check, even though its calling functions
will have already done this.  This removes such check, renames it
to screen_process() and updates its usage elsewhere.

Change-Id: I480a4560a45b131a95c1b2d2d2379aeba542a9bc

commit_message:
Define experimental check-heat-dsvm-functional-postgres

This allows in-tree functional tests to be run against a postgres
devstack, but only on-demand in the experimental pipeline.

As a consequence, check-heat-dsvm-functional is renamed to
check-heat-dsvm-functional-mysql.

Change-Id: I2617f969e1832c9d78348f9c56e4b3b50f3633c7

Add kilo to features.yaml

So that we are prepared when the first proposed/kilo branches roll out
add some kilo data to features.yaml today.

commit_message:
Havana branches are dead, remove havana from d-g

We EOLed, tagged, then deleted the stable/havana branches everywhere.
Clean havana out of devstack-gate as this config is no longer necessary.

Note this adds Juno specific test-features.sh tests because the havana
tests are no longer needed but we should continue to test that we
generate the proper feature lists for our stable branches.

Change-Id: Iea93ac03a9729cf6fe75a6410de4dec2c531f8d2

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Check for VPN Objects when deleting interfaces

When we delete Router interfaces/gateway,
we need to check if any VPN services are
associated with that router.

Closes-Bug:1261598

Change-Id: I7df2b8b130b47ec070d0b0a36b1a62df40532760

commit_message:
Stop running ceilometer mongodb jobs on icehouse

All of our icehouse tempest jobs run on precise, but precise's mongodb
is too old for ceilometer. For this reason stop trying to run the
ceilometer mongodb tests against icehouse changes.

Change-Id: I470bbba6eec8444444eebbece7b552cee619c3a0

commit_message:
Cleanup grenade machinery in prep for Juno

Over the Juno cycle we made changes to how we process grenade config in
devstack gate. We did so in a backward compatible way for our old jobs.
Clean up the now no longer needed backward compat code to make new Juno
grenade testing simpler.

Change-Id: I08736a5a1d3d55fe20b95c740e69f4557add46fc

commit_message:
Pass args to stress tox call

Tempest tox.ini stress section no longer hard-codes arguments.
Run a selection of stress tests for one hour each.

Change-Id: I0d63fca3f9d7833876b564aa72f8f0891adcb394

commit_message:
Don't stop update immediately on error

When an error occurs during a stack update operation,
don't immediately stop the operation. Instead,
wait up to 4 minutes for resources already in progress
to complete before forcibly cancelling them.

Change-Id: Ib089dbc675c519668a44d1b0e3214feca5079978
Closes-bug: #1381984
(cherry picked from commit ddd6fc16d765e9f5aff8d8e173402caa6de6196d)

commit_message:
Neutron OVS based Distributed Virtual Router

This blueprint spec provides information
about the Neutron OVS based Distributed
Virtual Router Implementation.

This changeset addresses gaps in the original
blueprint, in order to make it current to
upstream pushed code.

This blueprint addresses both the East-West routing
and North-South routing.

commit_message:
Wait for rabbitmq to respond to commands

Sometimes rabbitmq service starts but rabbitmq
server is not ready to accept requests. This

commit_message:
Wait for rabbitmq to respond to commands

Sometimes rabbitmq service starts but rabbitmq
server is not ready to accept requests. This
commit adds wait loop for rabbitmq and then
allows rabbitmq_* resources to work with
rabbitmq server.

Change-Id: Ic01773a4f84bbc1fa1a4139a0a6eb366191a8b9b
Closes-bug: #1377491

commit_message:
Clean up shell authentication

* Remove the auth option checks as the auth plugins will validate
  their own options
* Move the initialization of client_manager to the end of
  initialize_app() so it is always called.  Note that no attempts
  to actually authenticate occur until the first use of one of the
  client attributes in client_manager.  This leaves
  initialize_clientmanager() (formerly uathenticate_user()) empty
  so remove it.
* Remove interact() as the client_manager has already been created
  And there is nothing left.
* prepare_to_run_command() is reduced to trigger an authentication
  attempt for the best_effort auth commands, currently the only
  one is 'complete'.
* Add prompt_for_password() to ask the user to enter a password
  when necessary.  Passed to ClientManager in a new kward pw_func.

Bug: 1355838
Change-Id: I9fdec9144c4c84f65aed1cf91ce41fe1895089b2

commit_message:
Make hook elements depend on heat-config

This patch updates all of the specific configuration hook elements
so that they automatically pull in the heat-config element.
This is useful in that it minimizes what a DIB user must
explicitly list on the command line when building elements.

Change-Id: Ib890e5171e9836891074925fea88169c4276d333

commit_message:
Moves from markdown to rst

Changes format of files from markdown to reStructuredText
and adds the tox targets to verify the format and build
the html. Also adds bits and pieces needed to finish
bootstrapping the repository.

Change-Id: If559c21f19d7044a0d89b29e5743bf09c9da2ac1

This patch adds the @_retry_on_deadlock decorator
to _instance_update(), which has been observed to be
involved in some deadlock scenarios.  As it is the point
of transaction demarcation based on the presence of
get_session(), this is an appropriate point at which the
transaction can be re-attempted in the case of deadlock.

Closes-bug: 1375467

This patch adds the @_retry_on_deadlock decorator
to _instance_update(), which has been observed to be
involved in some deadlock scenarios.  As it is the point
of transaction demarcation based on the presence of
get_session(), this is an appropriate point at which the
transaction can be re-attempted in the case of deadlock.

Closes-bug: 1375467
Cherry-picked from: 68ed3c034ba1b0767694026000723e5255d24a64
'}]
commit_message:
Add @_retry_on_deadlock to _instance_update()

This patch adds the @_retry_on_deadlock decorator
to _instance_update(), which has been observed to be
involved in some deadlock scenarios.  As it is the point
of transaction demarcation based on the presence of
get_session(), this is an appropriate point at which the
transaction can be re-attempted in the case of deadlock.

Change-Id: Id2cfdc129ea3cfc787b73f1f3e9aa286a7c0229a
Closes-bug: 1375467
Cherry-picked from: 68ed3c034ba1b0767694026000723e5255d24a64

commit_message:
Tolerate null on Json db load

A icehouse->juno migration issue has surfaced where
resource.properties_data is null for existing resource records.

This change fixes the Json db type to treat None the same as
the serialized JSON 'null'.

Change-Id: Ia0b9a23a7798c95fbbcba439ffb8203b50367e7c
Closes-Bug: #1383505

commit_message:
Bump oslotest minimum requirements to 1.2.0

Since it was recently released, lets bump minimum version of
oslotest to 1.2.0. Some keystone related projects plan on
leveraging code that is 1.2.0 specific.

commit_message:
Enable H301

Fix all failures caused by H301 (Only one import per line).
Disable H302 and H304 checks which are enabled if H301 is enabled since
they cause too many failures for now.
H302 is "import only modules" - thus this fixes a few cases of this as
well (importing mock instead of "from mock import patch").

Change-Id: I899d00099cbd276f489b984d7993ae795a6e5ef4
Partial-Bug: #1337409

commit_message:
Unify distribution versions for Install Guide

Add version numbers for RHEL, CentOS, Fedora, openSUSE and SLES to
Install Guide.
Do not use codename for Debian in title and remove LTS from Debian
version.
Use version 7 for Debian.
Add missing text for SLES in intro.

Update Juno and trunk index pages and common appendix for the change.

Change-Id: Ie3938679f9a457aba7f71eda7911905aaa6659ef

Hi Matthew,

We would like to solve the problem of propagating the targets on all the hosts by having a periodic tasks fetching all the static targets from the hosts and then populating each host with what has been retrieved and rescan each host.
The price of the scan latency will not directly impact the user since this would be an async periodic operation.

This would solve the problem of vMotion (a vMotion might be a no-op if it happens before the periodic task but at some point it would happen), same thing for a new host added to the cluster.

Consequently, we want this patch (#97612) to make sure we pick the host where the VM is running in the case where the attach volume operation happens before the periodic task is triggered.

Let me know if that sounds good to you.

Thanks for the review'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-10 17:28:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

I had a quick flick through this. get_host_ref_for_vm() is obviously a problem, but the wider problem is that this change on its own doesn't fix iSCSI support in the vmware driver.

This change means that you can attach an iSCSI device to an instance and it will work initially. However, it will not continue to work if the VM is vMotioned. There's a follow-on patch to fix that, but it's not there yet and it remains a hard problem.

So we have some naval gazing to do. Do we want to have iSCSI work initially but unpredictably fail at some point in the future? Or do we want to leave it broken and not claim to support it until we've fixed it properly?"}, {'account_id': 8759, 'date': '2014-10-22 18:49:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandon this patch for now. We need to come with a complete solution to the problem'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-03 20:10:44.000000000', 'message': "VMware: get_host_ref() uses VM placement

Currently, vm_util.get_host_ref() doesn't take into account the VM
placement when returning the host: it currently returns the first host
found.
The behavior is not correct when the cluster contains more than one
host because the VM is not guaranteed to run on the host returned.

This patch fixes the issue by using the VM reference to find the host
where the VM is running.

Change-Id: Id1fe8aa5f1f3ecb0b52aa6d5543741c1ef71c82c
Closes-Bug: #1325789
"}, {'created': '2014-06-03 20:11:58.000000000', 'message': "VMware: get_host_ref() uses VM placement

Currently, vm_util.get_host_ref() doesn't take into account the VM
placement when returning the host: it currently returns the first host
found.
The behavior is not correct when the cluster contains more than one
host because the VM is not guaranteed to run on the host returned.

This patch fixes the issue by using the VM reference to find the host
where the VM is running.

commit_message:
VMware: Use the VM location to find iSCSI targets

When attaching an iSCSI volume, Nova triggers a HBA scan in order to
find the static targets and indirectly populates the SCSI topology in
vCenter.
The current implementation takes the first host found as the host to
perform the scan. This doesn't take into account the fact that the VM
can run on another host. This is problematic because then the host
where the VM is running is not aware of the target that the VM is
supposed to be attached to.

This patch fixes the issue by using the instance to retrieve the host
where the VM is running instead of using the cluster reference.
Consequently, a NoValidHost exception is thrown if the instance
doesn't have a host to run on.

Change-Id: Id1fe8aa5f1f3ecb0b52aa6d5543741c1ef71c82c
Closes-Bug: #1325789

The use of _Lx is intented to do two things.  It makes it possible to identify which messages should go into which catalog and it identifies which catalog to use when translating the message.  The goal being to enable prioritization of message translation.

The direction that @Duncan and I were looking at was two fold.  Use a tool @Duncan has that doesn't require the use of _Lx to identify the messages, but looks at how they are used.  And use it in conjunction with a LogAdapter that directs the messages to the right catalog.

While I think the hacking check is useful. It seems like the right solution would be to remove the _Lx definitions from the cinder/i18n.py integration module and replace them with a comment that they have been removed.  Then it would fail if someone tries to import them."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2014-10-20 15:28:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Jim, I agree that removing the definition from cinder/i18n.py is a good idea, but doesn't prevent users from importing the definitions in other ways.  So, I think keeping this hacking check and creating another patch to remove the definition is the most sensible way to go.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2014-10-20 17:06:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Jay, that sounds like a good way to do it.  It seems like once everyone moves to the oslo.i18n library, it would be a valuable general check to ensure that the _, _L* aren't imported from anywhere other than the project's i18n integration i18n.py.   That general check, which would be more complex than this one, would then automatically enforce it if you removed them from your integration library."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:09:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I have pushed up a changer under https://review.openstack.org/130026 to remove definition of _LC, _LI, _LW and _LE as was recommended here.'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2014-10-21 20:45:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Duncan: yes, I was thinking something different from what that actually describes when I wrote it, feel free to ignore that part.

@Jay: The main point still stands -- it would be nice to document the implications (somewhere) of deciding we are going to be different from the rest of OpenStack on this.'}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2014-10-21 23:02:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Eric,

Ok, would it be sufficient if Jim and I put together an answer to your question and documented it in cinder/i18n.py or would you prefer it be documented here with the hacking check?'}, {'account_id': 170, 'date': '2014-10-22 15:27:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

This is not a decision we're going to make within Cinder. I would recommend talking to others on the OpenStack ML to get a consensus on your problems with the markers and how they can be improved."}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2014-10-22 18:13:22.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

We have decided that we actually will be using the Log Level Markers so I am abandoning this change.'}]

commit_message:
Add hacking check for use of log level markers

Since we have decided to not use log level markers in Cinder
for the time being I am adding a hacking check to make sure
that people don't start adding them.

Change-Id: I4f26b8ba059ad0028f1c4cd699b706525b13c347

commit_message:
Remove unused _LW, _LC, _LI and _LE from i18n.py

As was recommended during the review of a related patch
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/129297) I am removing the
definition of _LW, _LC, _LI and _LE from cinder/i18n.py.  This
ensures, along with the change proposed in 129297, that users will
not be able to import/use the _L* log level markers.

Change-Id: Idadfbffd4e1425babb5e91416614638153ca6105

have you considered to put this under metrics mechanism?'}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2014-07-02 03:39:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi @Jay, this is not related to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/90647/, I read that spec[90647] carefully, it only refer to some CPU weights, I don't think it can meet my requirement, light workload host refer not only CPU utilization but also local disk IO and network utilization, and I don't think simple accumulation can help me to choose light workload host, like this: cpu + disk io + network = host weight, instance io ops number is more easy to understand, we don't need to add a group compute monitor(disk, network and so on).

Hi @yunhong-jiang, thanks for your suggestion, I ever consider metrics weighter, but currently nova had recorded num_io_ops in host state, why we don't use it directly? Metrics weighter is good feature, but why we must add a group compute monitor(disk, network) for same purpose like 'num_io_ops'?

Thanks for your review."}, {'account_id': 8276, 'date': '2014-07-14 08:17:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-14 08:17:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

1.- It goes against the documentation [1], that states the following:

"""
A weigher is a way to select the best suitable host from a group of valid hosts
by giving weights to all the hosts in the list.

In order to prioritize one weigher against another, all the weighers have to
define a multiplier that will be applied before computing the weight for a
node. 
"""

Therefore, the weigher must return the best host from the hosts being weighed
regardless of the multiplier, that will be used only to prioritize the
weigher against the other weighers.

This is what other weighers are doing (ram, metrics, cell ram, cell mute child,
cell weight offset).

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/nova/devref/filter_scheduler.html#weights

2.- Even if (1) would be accepted, with my operator hat on this is something
totally counter-intuitive. It is natural to expect that weighers will give the
highest weight to the best host (in this case the host with less IO ops).

Figure out that we finish with several weighers, each one with a different
behaviour for their multipliers. It will be a mess to configure all of them:
you'll need to check the documentation for each of the multipliers and for
sure it will be an error prone process.

As a conclusion, I think that you should modify the weigher so that you return
the winner, regardless of the multiplier. Otherwise it will go against the
documentation and is counter intuitive. You can return whatever value you want
as the weight, since the normalization will transform it into a value between
[0.0, 1.0].'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-14 07:58:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1
